1:11:28.560 --> 1:11:29.971
Let's see you now.

1:11:31.520 --> 1:11:32.965
Let's see you now.

1:11:33.640 --> 1:11:35.324
<i>It's scared of us, you know?</i>

1:11:36.720 --> 1:11:39.246
I can feel that. I swear to God I can.

1:11:44.680 --> 1:11:45.920
I want to kill It.

1:11:52.720 --> 1:11:53.721
Help me.

1:12:02.920 --> 1:12:04.251
Please, help me.

1:12:05.640 --> 1:12:06.641
Help me.

1:13:20.680 --> 1:13:22.489
<i>Balki. Balki, let go.</i>

1:13:22.640 --> 1:13:24.085
<i>You let go.
You let go first.</i>

1:13:24.240 --> 1:13:27.722
<i>All right, Balki.
On the count of three, we'll both let go.</i>

1:13:27.920 --> 1:13:30.082
<i>Ready?
One, two, three.</i>

1:13:35.640 --> 1:13:36.641
Oh...

1:13:37.120 --> 1:13:38.849
We got a letter from Mom today.

1:13:39.360 --> 1:13:41.567
She asked when we were going to
make her a grandma.

1:13:42.120 --> 1:13:45.169
The woman's uncanny.
I was just thinking the same thing myself.

1:13:46.840 --> 1:13:47.921
<i>Well, I was, really.</i>

1:13:52.520 --> 1:13:55.569
Does she know I'm a sex maniac
and you prefer <i>Perfect Strangers</i>, huh?

1:13:55.720 --> 1:13:58.007
You want to pay attention to me?

1:14:02.840 --> 1:14:04.046
Don't move.

1:14:08.320 --> 1:14:10.561
Uris residence. Stan speaking.
This better be good.

1:14:10.720 --> 1:14:12.848
<i>Hello, Stan. It's Mike Hanlon.</i>

1:14:13.480 --> 1:14:15.050
- Who did you say?
<i>- Mike Hanlon.</i>

1:14:15.200 --> 1:14:16.690
- Mike Hanlon?
<i>- Yeah.</i>

1:14:18.520 --> 1:14:19.885
I'll be damned.

1:14:20.040 --> 1:14:22.042
<i>Stan, It's come back.</i>

1:14:23.360 --> 1:14:26.125
- Are you sure?
<i>- Yeah, I'm sure.</i>

1:14:26.320 --> 1:14:28.971
<i>- You understand? I am sure.</i>
- No, I understand.

1:14:29.240 --> 1:14:31.004
<i>Look, I hope you know
how hard it is to call...</i>

1:14:31.160 --> 1:14:32.366
I get the picture.

1:14:32.520 --> 1:14:34.682
<i>Can you make it, Stan? Please.</i>

1:14:35.520 --> 1:14:38.729
No, I can't absolutely promise that.

1:14:38.880 --> 1:14:41.611
<i>- Don't you remember, Stan?</i>
- But I'll... I'll certainly consider it.

1:14:41.760 --> 1:14:44.286
<i>- Don't you remember your promise?</i>
- What? Yes, Mike.

1:14:44.440 --> 1:14:46.647
<i>- You promised.</i>
- Yes, I remember.

1:14:47.120 --> 1:14:48.326
<i>I hope you come.</i>

1:14:48.480 --> 1:14:50.130
- Good bye.
<i>- Bye, Stan.</i>

1:14:52.560 --> 1:14:54.164
<i>I can't even ski
in my own living room.</i>

1:14:55.400 --> 1:14:57.004
<i>This isn't going to work.</i>

1:14:57.160 --> 1:14:58.685
Who was it, honey?

1:14:58.920 --> 1:14:59.967
<i>But I'm glad.</i>

1:15:00.200 --> 1:15:02.248
<i>Now you can make a new beginning
and tell Jennifer the truth.</i>

1:15:02.440 --> 1:15:03.441
Stan?

1:15:04.360 --> 1:15:05.361
No one.

1:15:07.240 --> 1:15:08.321
No one, really.

1:15:10.240 --> 1:15:12.083
I think I'll take a bath.

1:15:13.240 --> 1:15:14.366
Now?

1:15:37.400 --> 1:15:42.247
<i>A scout is trustworthy,
loyal, helpful, friendly, courteous, kind,</i>

1:15:42.400 --> 1:15:44.562
<i>obedient, cheerful, thrifty,</i>

1:15:44.720 --> 1:15:47.849
brave, clean and reverent.

1:15:48.960 --> 1:15:51.691
- You okay?
- I think this is crazy.

1:15:59.400 --> 1:16:02.802
One out of 10.
You're worse than I am, kiddo.

1:16:03.200 --> 1:16:05.965
At this rate, we might as well
let that damn clown take us one by one.

1:16:06.160 --> 1:16:07.321
Beep, beep, Richie.

1:16:08.080 --> 1:16:10.606
Who's left? Ben? Bev?

1:16:10.800 --> 1:16:13.121
Yeah, and one of them
better be good, Bill,

1:16:13.280 --> 1:16:15.681
'cause you're in the lead right now
with a pathetic three out of 10.

1:16:15.880 --> 1:16:17.484
Richie, will you please shut up?

1:16:18.480 --> 1:16:21.211
- You know, you don't stutter all the time.
- Ladies first.

1:16:45.360 --> 1:16:48.364
Ten out of 10.
Don't think I need to shoot.

1:16:48.800 --> 1:16:50.802
It's like it's supposed to be Bev.

1:16:51.520 --> 1:16:53.204
Yeah.
- Yeah.

1:16:53.480 --> 1:16:55.209
- Whoa.
- This is still crazy.

1:16:56.440 --> 1:16:58.681
No, it's not.
- I'm with Stan.

1:16:59.400 --> 1:17:01.402
So what if I can shoot good?

1:17:01.760 --> 1:17:03.046
You think a handful of stones
are going to stop...

1:17:03.200 --> 1:17:04.247
Show them, Richie.

1:17:05.200 --> 1:17:07.965
My mother's earrings, baby. Solid silver.

1:17:08.120 --> 1:17:11.044
That's just stuff in movies.
What good is it going to do against...

1:17:11.200 --> 1:17:15.125
They're silver. They can kill It.
Believe, Stannie. We have to.

1:17:22.800 --> 1:17:25.167
<i>"On my honor,
I will do my best</i>

1:17:25.400 --> 1:17:28.688
<i>"to do my duty to God and my country,</i>

1:17:29.240 --> 1:17:34.121
"to help other people at all times,
keep myself physically strong,

1:17:34.280 --> 1:17:37.568
"mentally awake and morally..."

1:17:37.720 --> 1:17:38.881
Maybe this isn't
such a good idea.

1:17:39.040 --> 1:17:41.202
- What are you mumbling about?
- Shh.

1:17:46.520 --> 1:17:47.851
Now, listen.

1:17:49.040 --> 1:17:50.610
You guys don't have to do this.

1:17:50.760 --> 1:17:53.240
My dad says you have to know
when to take a stand.

1:17:57.760 --> 1:17:59.364
Lucky seven, Stannie.

1:18:00.440 --> 1:18:01.646
I said I was in.

1:18:02.040 --> 1:18:05.487
Yeah, you think we're going to
let you have all the fun there, Billy-boy?

1:18:06.280 --> 1:18:07.281
Eddie?

1:18:07.760 --> 1:18:09.922
I'm with my friends. Right?

1:18:12.840 --> 1:18:14.080
Give me that.

1:18:17.160 --> 1:18:19.162
Yuck. It tastes like battery acid.

1:19:06.840 --> 1:19:09.764
- Where are they going?
- Down in the sewer, stupid.

1:19:09.920 --> 1:19:10.921
Yeah.

1:19:11.280 --> 1:19:12.281
And guess what?

1:19:14.120 --> 1:19:15.963
They're not coming back out.

1:19:43.920 --> 1:19:45.490
You mean
we gotta go down there?

1:19:46.000 --> 1:19:50.050
Stan, if you don't want to go...
Now's the time to turn back.

1:19:53.880 --> 1:19:55.882
Great choice. Let's go.

1:20:32.880 --> 1:20:33.881
All right.

1:20:34.040 --> 1:20:35.041
They're going down into the pipes.

1:20:35.200 --> 1:20:36.884
Remember when we chased that dog
down in there?

1:20:37.040 --> 1:20:38.087
Yeah.
- Okay.

1:20:38.240 --> 1:20:39.321
You go how we went.

1:20:39.520 --> 1:20:41.488
You'll come out ahead of them,
chase them back towards us.

1:20:41.640 --> 1:20:43.881
Me and Belch are gonna catch up to them.

1:20:44.040 --> 1:20:46.771
Hurry or there will be nothing
left for you.

1:20:48.920 --> 1:20:49.921
Go by myself, Henry?

1:20:50.080 --> 1:20:53.209
"Go by myself, Henry?"
Yeah, go by yourself.

1:20:53.360 --> 1:20:56.284
What are you afraid of, huh?
The boogeyman?

1:21:24.800 --> 1:21:25.961
Hardy-har-har.

1:21:26.280 --> 1:21:28.044
Yeah, well, at least we know
we're on It's trail.

1:21:28.200 --> 1:21:30.646
Maybe this is where it wants us to be.

1:21:30.800 --> 1:21:32.802
Eddie, which way is Derry?

1:21:36.320 --> 1:21:39.688
Okay. Look, Bev, you get up front
where you can get a clear shot.

1:21:39.840 --> 1:21:42.571
And you guys, stay together.
No stragglers.

1:23:08.960 --> 1:23:09.961
Hi, kid.

1:23:10.520 --> 1:23:12.249
I, uh, guess you're the first.

1:24:02.640 --> 1:24:04.244
- Who's missing?
- Stan.

1:24:04.400 --> 1:24:05.401
Oh, no!

1:24:13.000 --> 1:24:15.241
<i>Now, before you die,</i>

1:24:15.440 --> 1:24:17.886
I want you to think about
every rock you threw,

1:24:18.680 --> 1:24:20.330
<i>and everything you've said.</i>

1:24:20.880 --> 1:24:23.008
I want you to think about that
before you die.

1:24:32.160 --> 1:24:33.161
Hey, Henry.

1:24:40.200 --> 1:24:41.201
What was that?

1:25:15.480 --> 1:25:16.481
Belch!

1:25:18.520 --> 1:25:20.648
<i>God, he's not in there anymore.</i>

1:25:21.640 --> 1:25:22.801
Belch!

1:26:01.560 --> 1:26:02.686
Help!

1:26:07.360 --> 1:26:08.361
<i>It's Stan!</i>

1:26:08.520 --> 1:26:10.045
It's coming! It's coming!

1:26:13.760 --> 1:26:15.046
Hands, quick!

1:26:59.040 --> 1:27:01.247
Is that it? Did We do it?

1:27:01.480 --> 1:27:02.606
Look!

1:27:18.920 --> 1:27:22.163
Quick! Take hands
before we get lost in this stuff.

1:27:22.840 --> 1:27:24.171
Grab hold!

1:27:25.160 --> 1:27:26.650
Is everybody here?

1:27:27.480 --> 1:27:29.847
- I'm here. Stannie?
- Yeah.

1:27:30.000 --> 1:27:31.001
Richie?

1:27:31.400 --> 1:27:32.811
Yeah. Uh, Mike?

1:27:34.320 --> 1:27:35.651
Here.

1:27:35.800 --> 1:27:37.689
- Whose hand is this?
- Mine.

1:27:37.840 --> 1:27:39.330
That you, Ben?

1:27:39.720 --> 1:27:40.721
Yeah.

1:27:41.240 --> 1:27:43.402
Okay.
Whatever happens, hang on.

1:27:43.560 --> 1:27:46.689
It's not as strong as it thought it was,
or it could've killed us just then.

1:27:47.040 --> 1:27:48.724
We have to resist!

1:27:50.080 --> 1:27:53.801
<i>Bill! Bill!</i>

1:27:54.120 --> 1:27:55.360
Georgie?

1:27:56.240 --> 1:27:57.366
<i>No, Bill!</i>

1:27:58.680 --> 1:28:01.968
That's not George. Don't break the circle.

1:28:02.120 --> 1:28:03.201
<i>Bevy!</i>

1:28:04.280 --> 1:28:07.568
Bevy, what do you think you're doing
down here with these boys?

1:28:07.760 --> 1:28:09.250
Now, get home.

1:28:09.400 --> 1:28:12.165
Daddy? Daddy, I'm...

1:28:12.320 --> 1:28:13.970
<i>Wake up, hot stuff.</i>

1:28:14.320 --> 1:28:15.321
That ain't Daddy.

1:28:16.200 --> 1:28:17.361
There ain't nothing there.

1:28:23.240 --> 1:28:24.765
I said...

1:28:24.920 --> 1:28:28.925
I said there ain't nothing there.

1:28:33.800 --> 1:28:36.246
...I will do my best
to do my duty to God and my country.

1:28:36.400 --> 1:28:41.400
On my honor, I will do my best
to do my duty to God and my country.

1:28:58.320 --> 1:28:59.560
<i>Stan.</i>

1:28:59.720 --> 1:29:01.563
<i>Stanley, boy.</i>

1:29:01.720 --> 1:29:02.767
Ben?

1:29:08.680 --> 1:29:10.762
Stanley, resist!
That's it!

1:29:11.080 --> 1:29:14.448
Let go! Be afraid!

1:29:14.600 --> 1:29:16.011
Bev, the stones!

1:29:16.200 --> 1:29:19.602
You all taste so much better
when you're afraid!

1:29:19.760 --> 1:29:21.125
<i>Hurry, Bev, kill it!</i>

1:29:21.280 --> 1:29:22.441
"Kill"?

1:29:23.920 --> 1:29:25.046
<i>Me?</i>
Oh...

1:29:25.240 --> 1:29:27.402
<i>Oh, you are priceless, brat.</i>

1:29:27.600 --> 1:29:30.126
I am eternal, child.

1:29:31.120 --> 1:29:33.726
<i>I am the eater of worlds</i>

1:29:34.040 --> 1:29:35.485
and of children.

1:29:36.640 --> 1:29:39.723
And you are next.

1:29:44.960 --> 1:29:47.361
This is battery acid, you slime!

1:29:57.600 --> 1:29:58.601
Please, God.

1:30:07.000 --> 1:30:08.729
- YOUNG RITCHIE; Kill it! Kill it, Bev!
- Kill it! Kill, Bev!

1:30:10.040 --> 1:30:11.405
Kill it, Bev!
Do it!

1:30:22.440 --> 1:30:24.602
Help me! Help me!

1:30:39.200 --> 1:30:41.202
it's dead?
I don't think so.

1:30:41.360 --> 1:30:43.044
- We got to get out of here.
- We've got to go after it!

1:30:43.200 --> 1:30:45.043
No, it's dead.
- We have to make sure!

1:30:45.200 --> 1:30:47.248
- It sounded like it was dying.
- Yeah, what if it didn't?

1:30:59.720 --> 1:31:02.644
- it's over.
- It's over.

1:31:03.600 --> 1:31:04.601
Right?

1:31:20.880 --> 1:31:22.564
Swear to me...

1:31:24.120 --> 1:31:26.885
Swear to me that if it isn't dead,

1:31:28.000 --> 1:31:29.764
we'll all come back.

1:31:36.760 --> 1:31:38.125
I swear.

1:31:42.480 --> 1:31:43.766
I swear.

1:31:47.520 --> 1:31:48.885
I swear it.

1:31:58.560 --> 1:32:00.164
Yeah, I swear.

1:32:04.760 --> 1:32:06.489
I swear, too.

1:32:20.880 --> 1:32:21.961
I swear.

1:32:26.320 --> 1:32:27.810
Swear.

1:32:41.080 --> 1:32:42.320
Stannie?

1:32:43.520 --> 1:32:47.047
I'm coming upstairs to scrub your back

1:32:47.680 --> 1:32:49.444
and your chest.

1:32:50.200 --> 1:32:51.406
And...

1:32:57.040 --> 1:32:58.451
Stanley?

1:33:02.280 --> 1:33:03.691
Stanley?

1:33:06.880 --> 1:33:08.166
Stan?

1:34:08.560 --> 1:34:09.846
Here you go.

1:34:10.880 --> 1:34:14.282
- You sure you don't want me to wait?
- No, thanks, I'll walk back.

1:34:32.720 --> 1:34:33.767
Georgie.

1:34:36.600 --> 1:34:38.523
How could I have forgotten?

1:34:40.240 --> 1:34:41.730
I'm so sorry.

1:34:53.480 --> 1:34:54.845
Take your pick...

1:34:55.280 --> 1:34:58.409
Billy-boy.

1:34:59.880 --> 1:35:00.881
on!

1:35:01.720 --> 1:35:04.087
Except for the one on the end.

1:35:04.960 --> 1:35:06.610
That's already taken.

1:35:07.200 --> 1:35:08.247
<i>Sorry.</i>

1:35:10.480 --> 1:35:11.970
I remember you.

1:35:12.480 --> 1:35:14.448
<i>And I remember we beat you.</i>

1:35:16.280 --> 1:35:17.850
I'm not afraid of you.

1:35:21.840 --> 1:35:23.330
I'm not afraid of you.

1:36:27.960 --> 1:36:29.564
I know how old I look.

1:36:29.760 --> 1:36:31.842
It's just that I remember you as a kid.

1:36:32.320 --> 1:36:34.049
Welcome home, Bill.

1:36:35.960 --> 1:36:37.962
I only wish it was under happier...

1:36:38.840 --> 1:36:40.569
Come on, let's go out.

1:36:42.240 --> 1:36:44.561
It occurred to me in there
that I didn't create any more paranoia

1:36:44.720 --> 1:36:46.006
than we already have here.

1:36:46.160 --> 1:36:48.049
I got a taste of it myself, earlier.

1:36:48.440 --> 1:36:50.363
At least people seem to care now.

1:36:50.520 --> 1:36:52.249
Or maybe it's just that
I'm a grown-up now.

1:36:52.760 --> 1:36:54.524
I feel so thick, Mike.

1:36:54.680 --> 1:36:56.682
I don't remember much of it at all,
what we did.

1:36:57.480 --> 1:37:00.768
I don't even remember why I came back,
except for Georgie.

1:37:01.520 --> 1:37:03.966
I'll bet it doesn't all come back at once.

1:37:04.320 --> 1:37:05.651
How come you remember?

1:37:05.840 --> 1:37:07.683
I never left, how could I forget?

1:37:07.880 --> 1:37:10.724
All I do is look on the street corner
and there we were. Seven of us.

1:37:10.880 --> 1:37:12.086
Lucky seven.

1:37:13.240 --> 1:37:15.083
Oh, man, that just came back.

1:37:16.280 --> 1:37:17.441
Something else.

1:37:18.240 --> 1:37:20.163
- One of us lived around here.
- Right.

1:37:21.920 --> 1:37:22.921
Bev!

1:37:23.160 --> 1:37:24.525
Right down the street.

1:37:25.600 --> 1:37:26.601
Her father...

1:37:26.760 --> 1:37:29.764
She was poor. Her father was the janitor.
This was Poor Town.

1:37:30.480 --> 1:37:31.686
Yeah, still is.

1:37:38.320 --> 1:37:39.321
Yours?

1:37:40.800 --> 1:37:43.849
Hey, I'm a bachelor, Bill.
It's all I need.

1:37:44.120 --> 1:37:46.122
It's clean and better yet, it's paid for.

1:37:49.600 --> 1:37:50.761
Feeling hungry?

1:37:50.920 --> 1:37:53.287
Frankly, I haven't had an appetite
since you called.

1:37:53.440 --> 1:37:56.284
I've arranged
dinner tonight for all of us.

1:37:56.720 --> 1:37:58.165
Have you seen any of the others?

1:37:58.320 --> 1:38:02.291
No. But I've had a feeling all afternoon

1:38:02.600 --> 1:38:06.002
I could tell whenever one of us hit town.
I don't think we're all here, yet.

1:38:07.440 --> 1:38:08.487
No.

1:38:09.160 --> 1:38:10.321
You, too?

1:38:10.920 --> 1:38:12.809
Whatever it is, it's powerful stuff.

1:38:13.480 --> 1:38:15.130
Well, here's to remembering.

1:38:18.840 --> 1:38:19.841
What?

1:38:21.400 --> 1:38:24.449
Maybe this will stimulate
those old memory banks a little.

1:38:32.040 --> 1:38:33.166
Silver.

1:38:33.600 --> 1:38:35.921
Yep, I ran across it in the pawn shop
about a year ago.

1:38:36.320 --> 1:38:38.004
I don't know, something made me buy it.

1:38:38.520 --> 1:38:40.329
It's got a flat tire,
but that's all that's wrong with it.

1:38:40.760 --> 1:38:42.444
But here's the real kicker.

1:38:44.840 --> 1:38:47.810
I bought this tube repair kit on impulse.

1:38:49.000 --> 1:38:51.241
About three months before I saw this bike.

1:38:53.520 --> 1:38:56.763
There was some kind of force
guiding us that summer.

1:38:56.920 --> 1:38:59.969
I don't know if it came just to help us
or if we created it.

1:39:00.240 --> 1:39:02.607
<i>But maybe it's still here.</i>

1:39:04.720 --> 1:39:06.051
I'm going to change clothes.

1:39:44.480 --> 1:39:46.323
<i>Oh, come on!</i>

1:39:46.560 --> 1:39:49.131
Not the Paramount, you slimeballs!

1:39:49.480 --> 1:39:52.131
<i>Where are the people of this city
supposed to get their culture?</i>

1:40:08.080 --> 1:40:09.491
- May I help you?
- Mike Hanlon.

1:40:09.640 --> 1:40:11.529
He stepped out a short while ago.

1:40:12.080 --> 1:40:14.242
- I'm pretty sure he's coming back.
- Good.

1:40:15.080 --> 1:40:19.404
Uh... I'm gonna sit here
and I'm gonna wait here for him.

1:40:20.760 --> 1:40:22.762
Come on, Tozier, get a grip.

1:40:26.440 --> 1:40:29.125
You look like you could use this.
It's just water.

1:40:30.280 --> 1:40:31.327
Thank you.

1:40:40.240 --> 1:40:43.005
<i>A little young for you,
isn't she, Richie?</i>

1:40:44.400 --> 1:40:46.243
<i>Beep, beep, Richie.</i>

1:40:46.440 --> 1:40:48.090
I didn't hear that.

1:40:48.440 --> 1:40:49.566
I didn't!

1:40:50.320 --> 1:40:51.810
I beg your pardon?

1:40:52.200 --> 1:40:54.089
<i>Come On up, Richie!</i>

1:40:54.840 --> 1:40:57.650
I got a balloon for you.

1:40:58.680 --> 1:41:00.364
Don't you want a balloon?

1:41:03.160 --> 1:41:06.721
What's the matter, one balloon not enough?

1:41:07.200 --> 1:41:09.043
Try a bunch!

1:41:34.520 --> 1:41:35.931
Is everything all right?

1:41:36.200 --> 1:41:38.009
- Yes...
- Last chance, Tozier.

1:41:38.160 --> 1:41:40.925
Get out before it gets dark tonight.

1:41:41.480 --> 1:41:44.006
You're too old to stop me.

1:41:44.240 --> 1:41:46.322
You're all too old.

1:41:47.520 --> 1:41:49.921
- Tell Mike Hanlon if you see him...
- Excuse me, sir.

1:41:50.360 --> 1:41:52.886
Do you have Prince Albert in a can?

1:41:53.120 --> 1:41:54.246
You do?

1:41:54.480 --> 1:41:56.130
Well, you better let the poor guy out.

1:41:58.080 --> 1:42:01.209
Tell Mike Hanlon that I had to go.

1:42:01.560 --> 1:42:04.450
That I had to get cleaned up. Tell him.

1:42:05.120 --> 1:42:06.485
<i>Tell him.</i>

1:42:06.760 --> 1:42:09.127
Tell him I'll see him tonight.

1:42:09.280 --> 1:42:10.281
Get out!

1:42:10.920 --> 1:42:12.922
<i>Last chance, Tozier. Get out!</i>

1:42:13.280 --> 1:42:15.282
<i>Get out while you can.</i>

1:42:15.760 --> 1:42:17.728
<i>Excuse me, ma'am.</i>

1:42:17.880 --> 1:42:21.089
<i>Is your refrigerator running? It is?</i>

1:42:21.520 --> 1:42:24.490
<i>Well, you better catch it
before it runs away.</i>

1:42:49.760 --> 1:42:50.761
MIKE; Whoa!

1:43:07.200 --> 1:43:08.201
Whoa!

1:43:10.440 --> 1:43:12.442
All right!

1:43:31.320 --> 1:43:32.321
Son of a gun.

1:43:33.040 --> 1:43:35.611
Not just any cards, Bicycle.

1:43:36.560 --> 1:43:38.483
They always made the best noise.

1:43:50.440 --> 1:43:51.646
Bill?

1:43:54.400 --> 1:43:55.481
I see it.

1:44:03.200 --> 1:44:06.204
<i>All right, you follow up on this
Miller thing. I'll call Todd myself.</i>

1:44:06.360 --> 1:44:08.761
What about the engineer's report?

1:44:08.920 --> 1:44:10.081
What's that?

1:44:11.240 --> 1:44:14.926
You're breaking up, Fran.
I'll call you from the hotel.

1:44:26.440 --> 1:44:27.805
Pull over here, will you?

1:44:34.320 --> 1:44:35.560
Wait for me.

1:45:01.360 --> 1:45:03.567
You're it! You're it!

1:45:04.400 --> 1:45:06.402
You're dead, fat boy.
Come on!

1:45:06.880 --> 1:45:08.211
You're going to die!

1:45:10.280 --> 1:45:11.805
- Yeah!
- Get him!

1:45:15.240 --> 1:45:17.402
<i>You're dead! You're dead!</i>

1:45:17.600 --> 1:45:19.125
Run, fat boy!

1:45:22.680 --> 1:45:25.081
You're it, porky.
You're it!

1:45:25.760 --> 1:45:28.286
- Have a nice trip.
- See you later, porky.

1:45:37.440 --> 1:45:40.046
Hey, you okay, buddy?
My knee.

1:45:50.440 --> 1:45:52.761
Lucky for me you have that hankie thing.

1:45:53.120 --> 1:45:56.806
Be prepared.
Here, why don't you just keep it?

1:45:58.760 --> 1:46:00.524
I think I'll be okay now.

1:46:00.720 --> 1:46:03.291
Hang tough, champ. You're gonna make it.

1:46:06.440 --> 1:46:08.124
<i>Ben Hanscom!</i>

1:46:10.480 --> 1:46:12.482
<i>It's nice to see you again.</i>

1:46:14.320 --> 1:46:16.641
<i>What have you been up to all these years?</i>

1:46:25.920 --> 1:46:28.605
We can't wait
to get you down here with us.

1:46:30.440 --> 1:46:33.444
You're in my mind. Only in my mind.

1:46:44.480 --> 1:46:46.482
Any spare change, mister?

1:46:46.760 --> 1:46:49.240
Hey, who walked all over your grave?

1:46:50.040 --> 1:46:52.008
I wasn't going to hurt you.

1:46:52.680 --> 1:46:53.920
I don't even know you.

1:46:57.800 --> 1:46:58.847
Let's go.

1:47:05.360 --> 1:47:07.328
- Derry Inn, did you say?
- Yeah.

1:47:07.880 --> 1:47:09.882
Reliving your childhood down there?

1:47:10.760 --> 1:47:14.765
Something like that. Just saying hi
to some old ghosts, you know.

1:47:47.600 --> 1:47:49.762
Oh, hell. Time does go by.

1:47:56.440 --> 1:47:57.680
<i>Here's that prescription.</i>

1:47:59.440 --> 1:48:00.646
How old are you now, son?

1:48:01.720 --> 1:48:03.609
Eleven. Almost 12.

1:48:04.640 --> 1:48:07.041
Old enough. Come with me.

1:48:09.240 --> 1:48:10.241
Come on.

1:48:17.640 --> 1:48:19.961
Relax, Eddie. I'm not gonna bite you.

1:48:20.200 --> 1:48:23.921
Now, most of your troubles come from
you being so tight and stiff all the time.

1:48:24.120 --> 1:48:26.441
You take your asthma, for instance.

1:48:29.600 --> 1:48:31.602
Do you know what a placebo is, Eddie?

1:48:32.280 --> 1:48:33.281
I got to go.

1:48:33.520 --> 1:48:34.567
It's water, Eddie.

1:48:34.760 --> 1:48:37.206
Water with a squirt of camphor
to make it taste like medicine.

1:48:37.400 --> 1:48:38.401
No.

1:48:38.640 --> 1:48:41.849
Your doctor is weak and your mother
is determined that you're ill.

1:48:42.000 --> 1:48:43.923
And you, my friend,
are caught in the middle.

1:48:44.480 --> 1:48:48.405
It's all a lie, a great big lie!
I do have asthma. I do!

1:48:51.720 --> 1:48:52.926
<i>Sir?</i>

1:48:54.120 --> 1:48:55.645
Your prescription.

1:48:59.800 --> 1:49:03.009
Nothing like a good pull
on the old lung-sucker, huh?

1:49:04.640 --> 1:49:05.641
Thank you.

1:49:05.960 --> 1:49:09.487
<i>Junior, bring me a cigar.</i>

1:49:09.800 --> 1:49:11.484
You know you can't have one, Granddad.

1:49:14.240 --> 1:49:15.446
Mr. Keene?

1:49:19.760 --> 1:49:21.808
Mr. Keene. Hello.

1:49:23.200 --> 1:49:25.282
Cigar for the old man?

1:49:25.480 --> 1:49:27.289
I'm sorry. I don't have any.

1:49:27.440 --> 1:49:30.569
I'm Eddie Kaspbrak, Sonia Kaspbrak's son.

1:49:31.320 --> 1:49:33.243
How about some licorice?

1:49:33.680 --> 1:49:36.081
I was always partial to licorice.

1:49:38.840 --> 1:49:41.571
Mr. Keene, I just wanted to thank you

1:49:41.760 --> 1:49:44.206
for trying to tell me the truth
a long time ago.

1:49:49.280 --> 1:49:51.965
You look a little peaked, sonny.

1:49:54.680 --> 1:49:55.841
I'd better go.

1:49:56.000 --> 1:49:57.240
Hydrox.

1:49:58.400 --> 1:49:59.401
What?

1:49:59.920 --> 1:50:01.888
H20.

1:50:02.440 --> 1:50:03.601
Water.

1:50:05.240 --> 1:50:07.288
<i>It's only water.</i>

1:50:07.960 --> 1:50:10.327
It's all in your head, sonny.

1:50:11.600 --> 1:50:13.602
You do remember me.

1:50:13.840 --> 1:50:14.841
Oh, Mr. Keene...

1:50:16.600 --> 1:50:17.931
Mr. Keene?

1:50:18.200 --> 1:50:21.522
Get out of Derry while you still can.

1:50:21.880 --> 1:50:23.530
Mr. Keene, please.

1:50:24.040 --> 1:50:26.122
Beware, little Eddie.

1:50:26.360 --> 1:50:29.125
Beware, girly-boy.

1:50:34.080 --> 1:50:36.048
No cigar, sonny.

1:50:36.760 --> 1:50:39.730
<i>I was always partial to licorice.</i>

1:51:19.240 --> 1:51:22.084
I'm sorry, I must have rung the
wrong bell. I was looking for Marsh.

1:51:22.320 --> 1:51:23.321
- Marsh?
- Yes.

1:51:23.520 --> 1:51:26.000
There's no Marsh here. Unless...

1:51:27.080 --> 1:51:28.684
You don't mean Alvin Marsh?

1:51:29.240 --> 1:51:30.571
Yes, my father.

1:51:30.880 --> 1:51:32.325
Oh, Miss...

1:51:32.720 --> 1:51:35.121
I hate to be the one to have
to tell you this, a stranger,

1:51:35.280 --> 1:51:37.408
but your father's been dead
this last five years.

1:51:38.560 --> 1:51:39.766
But on the bell...

1:51:42.720 --> 1:51:43.721
Oh...

1:51:44.280 --> 1:51:46.442
Kersh. I thought it said "Marsh."

1:51:46.960 --> 1:51:49.645
I'm Mrs. Kersh.
I knew your father a little.

1:51:51.200 --> 1:51:53.885
- Come in. Let me give you tea.
- No, I couldn't.

1:51:54.280 --> 1:51:56.408
You could and you will. I insist.

1:52:09.800 --> 1:52:11.290
Feel free to look around.

1:52:12.160 --> 1:52:14.447
Perhaps you'd like to freshen up?

1:52:49.000 --> 1:52:52.209
<i>Did you fall
asleep in there? It's teatime.</i>

1:52:57.360 --> 1:52:58.691
Tea.

1:52:59.320 --> 1:53:00.685
Tea would be nice.

1:53:02.160 --> 1:53:04.128
I love what you've done with the place.

1:53:04.360 --> 1:53:06.886
It's so different, so cozy.

1:53:07.160 --> 1:53:08.844
How kind you are, miss.

1:53:09.360 --> 1:53:12.204
I call all the pretty young girls "Miss".
Don't take offense.

1:53:12.600 --> 1:53:13.761
No.

1:53:23.280 --> 1:53:26.045
Well, go on, dear,
drink it while it's nice and hot.

1:53:40.560 --> 1:53:42.642
Don't trouble your
pretty little head, dear.

1:53:42.920 --> 1:53:44.285
I'll get it.

1:53:45.040 --> 1:53:47.042
It did say "Marsh" on the doorbell.

1:53:47.680 --> 1:53:50.081
If you're wise, you'll run, dear, run.

1:53:50.520 --> 1:53:52.921
Because to stay will mean
worse than your death.

1:53:53.080 --> 1:53:54.889
They float down there.

1:53:56.240 --> 1:53:57.321
<i>They float.</i>

1:54:00.560 --> 1:54:03.643
I worry about you, Bevy. I worry a lot.

1:54:06.040 --> 1:54:08.327
It won't do you any good to run, Bevy.

1:54:10.920 --> 1:54:13.764
You're not real! You're not real!

1:54:18.120 --> 1:54:19.281
Beep, beep!

1:55:11.480 --> 1:55:13.209
<i>I told you the first time
you introduced me to him</i>

1:55:13.360 --> 1:55:14.850
<i>that he was a twit, Audra.</i>

1:55:15.000 --> 1:55:16.001
<i>Do you remember?</i>

1:55:16.160 --> 1:55:17.844
Greco, I didn't ask you over
to insult Bill.

1:55:18.000 --> 1:55:20.480
- How dare he do this to me.
- Come on.

1:55:20.720 --> 1:55:23.041
You've been complaining about him
ever since we started this picture.

1:55:23.280 --> 1:55:25.760
He'll never work in movies again.
I suppose you know that.

1:55:26.280 --> 1:55:29.841
If you could have seen his face.
It was frightening.

1:55:30.720 --> 1:55:34.611
Nothing like a little crisis to bring
the estranged couple closer together, eh?

1:55:35.600 --> 1:55:38.604
Or perhaps pull them farther apart,
if the gods are smiling.

1:55:38.840 --> 1:55:39.887
Greco, please.

1:55:40.120 --> 1:55:44.125
I'm simply pointing out that this
could be a blessing in disguise.

1:55:45.040 --> 1:55:47.361
Would you consider giving me a few days?

1:55:48.600 --> 1:55:51.285
I shall pretend I didn't hear that, Audra.

1:55:52.080 --> 1:55:55.323
I can replace your imbecilic husband.
I cannot replace you.

1:55:57.360 --> 1:55:59.249
Don't even think about leaving, Audra.

1:56:00.240 --> 1:56:03.084
<i>You've worked very hard
to get where you are. Very hard.</i>

1:56:03.480 --> 1:56:05.562
I know you'd do nothing
to jeopardize that.

1:56:05.960 --> 1:56:09.123
Or to damage
our professional relationship.

1:56:09.840 --> 1:56:11.968
Or to turn a friend overnight
into a violent enemy,

1:56:12.120 --> 1:56:14.202
ready to crucify you at any cost.

1:56:18.720 --> 1:56:20.449
But there's no need to talk about that.

1:56:23.120 --> 1:56:24.770
See you tomorrow.

1:56:42.080 --> 1:56:44.242
International reservations, please.

1:56:44.880 --> 1:56:48.282
Yes, I'd like a seat on your next
flight to the United States.

1:57:09.480 --> 1:57:11.926
Excuse me,
I'm looking for the Hanlon party.

1:57:14.880 --> 1:57:16.291
- Eddie?
- Ben?

1:57:16.720 --> 1:57:18.961
- Eddie Kaspbrak.
- Haystack!

1:57:20.560 --> 1:57:23.211
- What happened to the rest of you?
- Gone but not forgotten.

1:57:23.400 --> 1:57:24.401
Hey. buddy!

1:57:27.640 --> 1:57:28.687
Oh, my God.

1:57:31.240 --> 1:57:33.322
Where's Richie Tozier
when you need a good line?

1:57:33.680 --> 1:57:35.887
- Ben?
- I'm afraid so, Bill.

1:57:36.040 --> 1:57:38.202
I can't believe it. Look at you.
Hey, Bill.

1:57:38.400 --> 1:57:40.801
Hey.
Michael, God.

1:57:41.120 --> 1:57:43.600
Mike, is that you?
Such as I am, Haystack.

1:57:48.800 --> 1:57:50.404
Hey, listen. Who wants a drink?

1:57:50.720 --> 1:57:52.290
- Set them up.
- I'll have one.

1:57:52.440 --> 1:57:54.010
<i>What is this?
That's my dog.</i>

1:57:54.160 --> 1:57:56.640
<i>I'll have</i> a <i>club soda, okay?
This is pretty good.</i>

1:58:03.040 --> 1:58:05.725
Come on, Tozier, don't let them
see you like this, get a grip, man.

1:58:05.920 --> 1:58:07.968
That was a hallucination.
It was a flashback deal.

1:58:08.120 --> 1:58:10.327
It was too much fun in '67.
Just get ahold.

1:58:11.920 --> 1:58:13.206
You're working too hard, kid.

1:58:13.440 --> 1:58:14.680
Jeez, you guys.

1:58:15.840 --> 1:58:17.524
I got a toast. I propose...

1:58:17.680 --> 1:58:19.762
All right, who got bald, who got wrinkled,

1:58:19.920 --> 1:58:21.843
and how many of God's children got wings?

1:58:22.000 --> 1:58:23.604
- Beep, beep, Richie!
- Richie!

1:58:23.760 --> 1:58:25.410
Richie, beep, beep.
- Mike, hey!

1:58:29.000 --> 1:58:31.321
Hey, buddy, how are you?
Fine, fine. You?

1:58:32.040 --> 1:58:33.041
Beverly?

1:58:34.520 --> 1:58:36.727
What a bunch of handsome old men.

1:58:41.440 --> 1:58:42.441
EDDIE; Oh!

1:58:51.920 --> 1:58:53.251
Hi, good-looking.

1:58:53.560 --> 1:58:55.722
Oh, Richie.

1:58:56.200 --> 1:58:57.201
Oh...

1:58:58.560 --> 1:58:59.686
Eddie!

1:58:59.840 --> 1:59:03.242
I'd rather catch you than anybody else
in the whole world, Beverly Marsh.

1:59:06.440 --> 1:59:07.441
Oh...

1:59:08.640 --> 1:59:11.246
I just saw all of you standing there

1:59:11.400 --> 1:59:14.085
and so much came flooding back,
it was like a tidal wave.

1:59:14.640 --> 1:59:17.371
Oh, Mike.
What are we getting ourselves into?

1:59:20.680 --> 1:59:22.045
Hi, Bev.
Hey.

1:59:24.920 --> 1:59:26.922
Oh, I'm so proud of you.

1:59:27.840 --> 1:59:28.887
Where's...

1:59:41.520 --> 1:59:42.965
Are you all right, Bev?

1:59:44.360 --> 1:59:45.441
Yes.

1:59:46.760 --> 1:59:47.886
No. I...

1:59:49.680 --> 1:59:51.284
I saw something today.

1:59:51.760 --> 1:59:53.524
Same with me.
Oh, man!

1:59:53.960 --> 1:59:56.804
- What I saw at the library, whoa...
- Was it Pennywise?

1:59:57.440 --> 1:59:59.283
With both barrels, it was Pennywise.

1:59:59.440 --> 2:00:00.726
He's working on us already.

2:00:00.920 --> 2:00:03.446
- Trying to chip away.
- Maybe that means he's afraid.

2:00:03.600 --> 2:00:05.762
It. It's afraid.

2:00:06.040 --> 2:00:07.485
Oh, man. It!

2:00:07.800 --> 2:00:10.770
Help us remember, Mike.
Help us fill in the gaps.

2:00:10.960 --> 2:00:14.487
Yeah, please, because I don't know
what you are guys talking about.

2:00:16.840 --> 2:00:21.289
I can't remember much of anything
and when I try, it kind of clouds over.

2:00:23.160 --> 2:00:24.525
I mean, didn't you feel it?

2:00:24.960 --> 2:00:26.644
<i>As soon as I crossed the county line,</i>

2:00:26.800 --> 2:00:29.565
it was like this veil
dropped over my eyes.

2:00:30.160 --> 2:00:31.571
Maybe it's the water.

2:00:32.320 --> 2:00:34.163
The water? Maybe it's the sewer.

2:00:37.040 --> 2:00:39.042
This is battery acid, you slime!

2:00:42.960 --> 2:00:44.564
Eddie!
Take a breath, man. Breathe.

2:00:50.320 --> 2:00:51.731
I'm okay.

2:00:52.000 --> 2:00:54.731
I think I remember who Pennywise was now.

2:00:55.000 --> 2:00:57.526
Big white guy, red nose,

2:00:58.120 --> 2:01:01.761
about 75 feet tall,
mouth full of razor sharp teeth.

2:01:02.880 --> 2:01:04.530
Oh, Eddie.

2:01:08.640 --> 2:01:10.768
What the hell is happening, you guys?

2:01:11.360 --> 2:01:13.249
What is going on?

2:01:15.960 --> 2:01:20.124
I'm sorry.
It was just a very vivid memory.

2:01:21.000 --> 2:01:24.322
I had forgotten that I stared
that creep right in the face.

2:01:24.560 --> 2:01:27.530
And you saved Stan's life.
You remember that part?

2:01:28.280 --> 2:01:29.361
Yeah.

2:01:30.520 --> 2:01:31.806
Yeah, now I do.

2:01:32.200 --> 2:01:34.885
Hey, speaking of Stan. Stan? Stan!

2:01:35.440 --> 2:01:37.090
Where is his royal straightness anyway?

2:01:37.240 --> 2:01:38.401
He wouldn't fink out on us,
would he, Mike?

2:01:38.600 --> 2:01:39.726
You talked to him, right?

2:01:39.960 --> 2:01:41.405
Yeah, I think he'll be along.

2:01:41.680 --> 2:01:44.650
I think we ought to go ahead without him.
When he gets here, we can fill him in.

2:01:44.840 --> 2:01:46.410
Come on, Mike, talk to us,
help us remember.

2:01:46.560 --> 2:01:48.403
No. Wait a minute.
I don't know about you guys,

2:01:48.560 --> 2:01:50.722
but this is the first time
since I got here that I feel good.

2:01:50.880 --> 2:01:53.486
I mean, I feel halfway safe. Come on.

2:01:54.040 --> 2:01:55.326
Let's have a couple of drinks,

2:01:55.480 --> 2:01:57.847
chew on some good food,
have a couple of chucks.

2:01:58.000 --> 2:01:59.206
And letâ€™s just leave
the wolf out the door.

2:01:59.400 --> 2:02:01.482
Spoken like a real loser, Richie.

2:02:01.640 --> 2:02:03.688
Hey, to the Loser's Club.

2:02:03.920 --> 2:02:06.571
- All right!
- To the Loser's Club.

2:03:19.960 --> 2:03:21.485
Talking about your wives?

2:03:21.800 --> 2:03:24.041
How many times have you been
to the altar, Richie?

2:03:24.200 --> 2:03:27.044
Four or five.
Who the hell keeps count?

2:03:27.200 --> 2:03:29.123
Women all want the same thing.
No offense, Bev.

2:03:29.280 --> 2:03:32.921
None taken, creep.
Welcome to the fourth century.

2:03:33.080 --> 2:03:34.411
What about you, Ben, you married?

2:03:34.560 --> 2:03:37.484
Nope, I've dodged the bullet
a number of times, now.

2:03:37.680 --> 2:03:39.284
How about you, Eddie?
<i>Me?</i>

2:03:40.000 --> 2:03:42.287
Yeah, I'm seeing this
really wonderful woman,

2:03:42.440 --> 2:03:44.920
but with the business and all,
I really don't have too much time.

2:03:45.280 --> 2:03:48.841
You take it from me, spaghetti man,
better dead than wed.

2:03:49.080 --> 2:03:51.082
Any little crumb
snatchers for you, Richie?

2:03:51.240 --> 2:03:52.526
None that I know of.

2:03:52.920 --> 2:03:54.684
<i>How about you, Bev?</i>
What?

2:03:55.520 --> 2:03:57.648
- How about you?
- Oh, uh...

2:03:58.280 --> 2:03:59.520
Well, I live with a...

2:04:00.200 --> 2:04:01.964
No, I'm not married.

2:04:03.440 --> 2:04:05.681
Richie, what ever happened
to those glasses?

2:04:05.880 --> 2:04:06.961
Contact lenses.

2:04:07.200 --> 2:04:10.409
Richie, for the number of times
you broke those glasses of yours,

2:04:10.600 --> 2:04:13.570
you should have had stock in
an adhesive tape company.

2:04:13.920 --> 2:04:15.524
Me and Henry Bowers.

2:04:18.040 --> 2:04:20.247
Somebody please tell me
he was hit by a freight train

2:04:20.400 --> 2:04:21.731
and put out of his misery.

2:04:21.880 --> 2:04:25.009
No such luck. You wanna see Henry Bowers
you'll find him up at Juniper Hills.

2:04:25.160 --> 2:04:28.562
Ever since the trial, where he confessed
to all the murders of all the children.

2:04:28.720 --> 2:04:31.803
- He was down there with us in the sewers.
- That creep was gonna kill Stan.

2:04:31.960 --> 2:04:33.405
He was going to kill us all.

2:04:33.560 --> 2:04:36.723
I remember when they pulled him out,
his hair had turned white.

2:04:36.880 --> 2:04:39.360
- He was babbling about a bright light.
- And a clown.

2:04:39.520 --> 2:04:41.010
And no one believed him.

2:04:41.200 --> 2:04:42.725
Except when he said
he killed all the kids.

2:04:42.880 --> 2:04:45.565
<i>And we didn't say anything.</i>
Not a word.

2:04:46.360 --> 2:04:49.569
But it was the killer and we stopped it.

2:04:50.400 --> 2:04:51.731
We thought we did.

2:05:01.920 --> 2:05:03.081
<i>Henry.</i>

2:05:04.320 --> 2:05:05.765
<i>Henry Bowers.</i>

2:05:10.880 --> 2:05:12.928
Up here, sharp stuff.

2:05:15.400 --> 2:05:16.481
<i>Up here!</i>

2:05:17.600 --> 2:05:19.807
You helped me once. Remember?

2:05:20.320 --> 2:05:21.924
You chased those brats.

2:05:22.080 --> 2:05:24.924
Almost got them, Henry. Almost.

2:05:25.840 --> 2:05:27.285
Don't you want another chance?

2:05:28.600 --> 2:05:31.331
<i>You've got to go back and finish the job.</i>

2:05:31.800 --> 2:05:34.770
<i>You've got to go back to Derry
and kill them all.</i>

2:05:34.960 --> 2:05:36.962
<i>For me, Henry.</i>

2:05:37.440 --> 2:05:38.965
<i>Kill them all.</i>

2:05:39.440 --> 2:05:41.442
Henry, kill them all.

2:05:41.600 --> 2:05:46.049
Kill them all. Kill them all.

2:05:46.200 --> 2:05:47.440
Kill them all.

2:05:47.640 --> 2:05:49.642
Kill them all!

2:05:53.080 --> 2:05:55.128
Well, sports fans,
this has been a real hoot,

2:05:55.840 --> 2:05:57.649
00 a.m.

2:05:57.800 --> 2:05:58.926
Richie, you're not leaving?

2:05:59.080 --> 2:06:01.162
Bev, girl, what do you want, an adventure?

2:06:02.080 --> 2:06:03.525
<i>You got some high-toned idea</i>

2:06:03.680 --> 2:06:05.489
<i>that you're gonna go relive
that old nightmare?</i>

2:06:05.640 --> 2:06:07.642
I love you, but count me out.

2:06:07.800 --> 2:06:09.484
I'm going to a hotel.
I'm gonna get some sleep,

2:06:09.640 --> 2:06:13.167
and in the morning, I get on a plane
and I'm out of here forever.

2:06:13.480 --> 2:06:16.006
- I will remember all of you very fondly.
<i>- Richie?</i>

2:06:16.360 --> 2:06:18.488
Hey, man, we're all scared.
It's nothing to be ashamed of.

2:06:18.640 --> 2:06:20.369
Maybe he's right.

2:06:22.480 --> 2:06:25.131
I mean, if you are talking about
going back into the sewer?

2:06:25.280 --> 2:06:26.520
<i>We don't know
what we're talking about yet</i>

2:06:26.720 --> 2:06:28.324
mainly because we haven't talked
about it yet.

2:06:28.480 --> 2:06:30.801
Yeah, suppose we give Mike
a chance to fill us in

2:06:30.960 --> 2:06:32.325
<i>before we scatter to the four winds.</i>

2:06:32.560 --> 2:06:33.686
Or is that too much trouble, Richie?

2:06:33.920 --> 2:06:35.763
All I'm saying is I'm gonna
go get some sleep.

2:06:36.000 --> 2:06:37.126
Is that too much to ask?

2:06:37.520 --> 2:06:39.010
Why don't we show Michael
a little courtesy...

2:06:39.160 --> 2:06:40.730
Guys! Guys, come, on!

2:06:40.880 --> 2:06:43.167
It's all right, Ben.
If Richie wants to go, he goes.

2:06:43.360 --> 2:06:46.091
Now, we all came here based
on the strength of a promise.

2:06:46.480 --> 2:06:49.609
As far as I'm concerned, everybody at
this table made good on that promise.

2:06:49.920 --> 2:06:51.524
Wherever we go from here,

2:06:52.240 --> 2:06:54.129
I have no expectations.

2:06:55.000 --> 2:06:56.570
Well said, Michael.

2:06:56.800 --> 2:06:58.450
It's all right.
It's taken care of, Richie.

2:06:58.840 --> 2:07:00.649
No, you can't do that.

2:07:00.880 --> 2:07:02.530
Guys, that's just the way it is.

2:07:05.520 --> 2:07:08.490
All right, then.
A toast to Mr. Michael Hanlon.

2:07:08.800 --> 2:07:11.804
<i>A man without whom none of this
would have been necessary.</i>

2:07:11.960 --> 2:07:13.246
I can see my fortune now,

2:07:13.400 --> 2:07:17.086
"You're gonna be eaten by a big,
greasy monster. Have a nice day."

2:07:44.200 --> 2:07:45.361
Dummy up, everybody.

2:07:54.240 --> 2:07:57.244
What is it? What's wrong?
Is something the matter?

2:07:58.080 --> 2:08:01.368
Our friend had an asthma attack,
but he's better now.

2:08:01.560 --> 2:08:05.121
I'm much better. Thank you. Thank you.

2:08:05.400 --> 2:08:07.084
Everything was okay?

2:08:07.280 --> 2:08:10.329
<i>Everything was fine, thank you.
Very fine. Thank you, Rose.</i>

2:08:18.160 --> 2:08:21.050
Guys, I'm not so sleepy anymore.

2:08:22.280 --> 2:08:23.486
Let's get the hell out of here.

2:08:38.280 --> 2:08:39.770
Is this the Uris residence?

2:08:40.200 --> 2:08:43.807
<i>Is Stan there?
This is Mike Hanlon, an old friend.</i>

2:08:45.320 --> 2:08:47.448
What are we supposed to do now?

2:08:47.800 --> 2:08:49.131
Hey, spaghetti man, no problem.

2:08:49.320 --> 2:08:51.926
A little soap, a little elbow grease
ought to clean it right up.

2:09:09.560 --> 2:09:12.564
<i>Why are we the only ones
that can see this?</i>

2:09:13.120 --> 2:09:17.523
Well now, there you've got me stumped.
Let's ask the answer man. Oh, Mike?

2:09:19.800 --> 2:09:21.131
Oh, Michel...

2:09:21.280 --> 2:09:22.281
<i>GarÃ§on?</i>

2:09:22.520 --> 2:09:24.761
Hold on just a sec. Hello, Stan?

2:09:25.120 --> 2:09:26.565
Mike Hanlon.

2:09:26.760 --> 2:09:29.445
Is this the Uris residence?
I'm trying to get ahold of Stan Uris.

2:09:29.800 --> 2:09:33.486
You tell that loser that if he hasn't
left already, he's a dead man.

2:09:33.640 --> 2:09:35.210
We all managed to show up.

2:09:35.360 --> 2:09:37.488
Boy, that matches your real hair.
Has anyone ever told you...

2:09:37.840 --> 2:09:39.604
Is anyone from out of town?

2:09:40.560 --> 2:09:42.847
I don't know about you.
I just flew in from LA, boy, and...

2:09:43.040 --> 2:09:44.530
<i>Boy, is my tail section tired.</i>

2:09:46.240 --> 2:09:47.730
Yeah, not a chance. We're hot tonight.

2:09:47.920 --> 2:09:51.367
It's great to be back in Derry,
breathing in that old Derry air.

2:09:51.960 --> 2:09:55.282
<i>I have never felt so much love in one
room in my entire life.</i>

2:09:55.840 --> 2:09:56.966
Eddie, get all their names

2:09:57.120 --> 2:09:58.485
I wanna put them on my Christmas mailer.

2:09:58.760 --> 2:10:01.843
No, Denbrough there, let's put him
on my Norman Mailer!

2:10:04.080 --> 2:10:07.562
I love this man.
He's like the brother I never had.

2:10:07.760 --> 2:10:10.047
Wait a minute.
He is the brother I never had.

2:10:10.480 --> 2:10:12.403
Beep, beep, Richie. Stan?

2:10:22.600 --> 2:10:23.726
Thank you.

2:10:27.160 --> 2:10:28.241
Stan is dead.

2:10:38.880 --> 2:10:42.089
He cut his wrists in the bathtub
right after I phoned him.

2:11:10.280 --> 2:11:12.965
Stan was the last one of us to see it
that summer.

2:11:13.920 --> 2:11:15.001
Remember?

2:11:15.160 --> 2:11:18.881
All summer long he kept saying,
"That just isn't empirically possible."

2:11:20.440 --> 2:11:22.966
Even seeing the clown
didn't make it real for him.

2:11:23.440 --> 2:11:24.487
Nothing did.

2:11:25.120 --> 2:11:27.122
<i>Until that afternoon in August.</i>

2:11:33.880 --> 2:11:36.929
<i>I remember
I was coming down Chestnut Street</i>

2:11:37.120 --> 2:11:40.408
<i>and I saw Stan running through the park
like something was after him.</i>

2:11:41.320 --> 2:11:42.481
<i>Go!</i>

2:11:42.720 --> 2:11:45.724
- Go!
- Hi yo, Silver. Away!

2:11:46.800 --> 2:11:48.643
<i>I can't honestly say
I saw anything that day.</i>

2:11:48.800 --> 2:11:50.484
<i>Stan's the one who saw it.</i>

2:11:52.160 --> 2:11:56.643
<i>I was pedaling too fast to turn around.
I didn't want to see it. Whatever it was.</i>

2:11:57.400 --> 2:12:00.370
<i>It took him hours to calm down enough
to tell me what happened.</i>

2:12:01.520 --> 2:12:05.002
<i>He said he was down
in Lampkin Park by a bird feeder.</i>

2:12:05.840 --> 2:12:07.285
<i>Watching birds.</i>

2:12:07.800 --> 2:12:09.643
<i>Like a good Boy Scout.</i>

2:12:09.840 --> 2:12:12.161
<i>Remember? He used to call it
"collecting birds".</i>

2:12:21.000 --> 2:12:22.684
<i>Stan...</i>

2:12:25.560 --> 2:12:26.686
<i>Stan...</i>

2:12:38.560 --> 2:12:41.370
<i>He said he didn't mean
to go into that house,</i>

2:12:42.720 --> 2:12:45.564
<i>but this voice kept whispering to him.</i>

2:12:46.160 --> 2:12:50.006
<i>And naturally, being Stan, he figured
there was a rational explanation.</i>

2:12:52.000 --> 2:12:53.047
Hello?

2:12:56.040 --> 2:12:57.485
<i>Stanley.</i>

2:12:59.040 --> 2:13:01.566
Yeah? I'm right here.

2:13:31.360 --> 2:13:32.691
He was trapped.

2:13:32.840 --> 2:13:34.251
<i>The only thing he could think of to do</i>

2:13:34.440 --> 2:13:36.681
<i>was to hold his bird book out
in front of him like a shield</i>

2:13:36.840 --> 2:13:39.605
<i>and say as loud as he could the names
of all the birds he could remember.</i>

2:13:39.760 --> 2:13:40.921
Longneck finch...

2:13:41.720 --> 2:13:43.563
Speckled grouse, Baltimore oriole...

2:13:46.440 --> 2:13:49.649
Great egret, hammerhead Woodpecker
and brown thrush.

2:13:52.800 --> 2:13:54.006
Brown thrush.

2:13:55.600 --> 2:13:57.807
The day that we went into the sewer

2:13:58.640 --> 2:14:00.130
Stan saw it.

2:14:01.520 --> 2:14:03.090
Face to face.

2:14:05.280 --> 2:14:09.649
Not the clown,
but he saw what was behind the clown.

2:14:12.040 --> 2:14:14.850
He ran up to me in school and he said,

2:14:15.040 --> 2:14:16.963
"I saw It, Eddie.

2:14:19.160 --> 2:14:21.003
"I looked right into its..."

2:14:22.360 --> 2:14:24.010
Some kind of lights.

2:14:26.960 --> 2:14:29.122
"I looked right into its deadlights."

2:14:31.160 --> 2:14:33.162
Then he said,

2:14:33.320 --> 2:14:36.802
and I hadn't thought of it until just now,
I swear, he said,

2:14:37.120 --> 2:14:40.761
"I looked into its deadlights
and I wanted to be there."

2:14:41.120 --> 2:14:42.326
Deadlights.

2:14:54.960 --> 2:14:57.566
I need a drink.
- Yeah, me, too.

2:14:58.560 --> 2:15:01.006
I'm sure I've got something here.
Anybody else?

2:15:01.200 --> 2:15:02.201
Yeah.

2:15:10.960 --> 2:15:12.041
Stan!

2:15:12.200 --> 2:15:14.680
Sorry, I'm late.
Well, let's see who's here.

2:15:18.000 --> 2:15:19.206
Billy-boy!

2:15:20.080 --> 2:15:22.890
Richie, you still here?
We never expected you to stick around.

2:15:23.040 --> 2:15:25.327
Nice nose job. No one would ever suspect.

2:15:25.800 --> 2:15:28.121
Haystack, putting on a little weight, huh?

2:15:28.520 --> 2:15:31.046
Speaking of dads, Bevy,
yours isn't worried about you anymore.

2:15:31.200 --> 2:15:32.611
<i>He loves your choice in men.</i>

2:15:33.040 --> 2:15:36.123
Wheezy, how's your sex life?
What's your sex life?

2:15:37.040 --> 2:15:38.724
Well, Mikey, you did it.
You got us all back here.

2:15:38.880 --> 2:15:41.008
<i>I guess it's 'cause it's
the only way you'd ever see us</i>

2:15:41.160 --> 2:15:43.686
<i>since you're so lame
you'd never leave this town.</i>

2:15:43.960 --> 2:15:47.009
I finally made it, guys.
I'm in the deadlights now.

2:15:47.360 --> 2:15:49.567
<i>And you know what?
It's true what they say.</i>

2:15:49.720 --> 2:15:52.644
We all float down here and you will, too.

2:15:52.960 --> 2:15:55.770
In fact, they all float!

2:15:56.240 --> 2:15:58.561
They all float!

2:16:19.480 --> 2:16:20.686
My God!

2:16:57.520 --> 2:16:58.567
All right.

2:16:58.760 --> 2:17:01.525
I don't know about the rest of you,
I'm getting real sick of this place.

2:17:01.800 --> 2:17:06.124
Now I'll listen to anything anybody has to
say, but could we do it someplace else?

2:17:06.360 --> 2:17:07.441
Please!

2:17:07.760 --> 2:17:09.171
Okay. Just help me with the stuff.

2:17:16.680 --> 2:17:17.806
Bill.

2:17:18.400 --> 2:17:19.526
What is it?

2:17:23.600 --> 2:17:25.045
"He thrusts his..."

2:17:29.160 --> 2:17:33.165
"He thrusts his fists against the post
and still insists he see the ghosts."

2:17:33.560 --> 2:17:35.403
That's all it says over and over
and over again.

2:17:37.600 --> 2:17:40.046
My mom gave me that to say

2:17:41.800 --> 2:17:45.043
to help with my stutter.

2:17:49.560 --> 2:17:51.642
No offense, pal, it ain't helping.

2:17:57.200 --> 2:17:59.851
Let's get the hell out of here.
What do you say?

2:18:22.200 --> 2:18:23.281
<i>Henry!</i>

2:18:24.200 --> 2:18:25.281
<i>Down here.</i>

2:18:32.960 --> 2:18:34.928
Belch? What are you doing down there?

2:18:35.880 --> 2:18:38.963
You got a problem in there
you need some help with, Henry?

2:18:42.960 --> 2:18:44.644
That's a good boy.

2:18:48.120 --> 2:18:49.929
<i>You don't
have to talk out loud, Henry.</i>

2:18:50.200 --> 2:18:53.568
I can hear you when you just think it
and they can't hear me at all.

2:18:54.120 --> 2:18:56.930
<i>What do you want?</i>
- Same thing you want.

2:18:57.440 --> 2:18:58.771
I want to pay them back.

2:19:00.600 --> 2:19:01.931
<i>Yeah, pay them back.</i>

2:19:02.440 --> 2:19:04.090
But you're gonna have to get out of here.

2:19:04.240 --> 2:19:05.810
You're gonna have to go back to Derry.

2:19:08.080 --> 2:19:11.641
I need you,
Henry. We all need you.

2:19:12.640 --> 2:19:14.085
<i>They can't hurt you.</i>

2:19:14.360 --> 2:19:17.330
We didn't think they could hurt us back
then either, but they did, didn't they?

2:19:17.760 --> 2:19:20.366
<i>Bested you all summer.
Don't talk about that.</i>

2:19:20.600 --> 2:19:23.604
I can take care of them
if they only half believe.

2:19:24.280 --> 2:19:26.123
But you, you're alive, Henry.

2:19:26.760 --> 2:19:28.125
You can get them
no matter if they believe,

2:19:28.280 --> 2:19:30.601
half believe or don't believe at all.

2:19:31.720 --> 2:19:34.451
One by one, Henry.

2:19:34.600 --> 2:19:36.125
<i>I can't get out of here.</i>

2:19:36.400 --> 2:19:39.085
<i>They got wires on the windows,</i>

2:19:40.240 --> 2:19:43.528
<i>and Koontz is on the door tonight.
Man, Koontz is the worst.</i>

2:19:44.160 --> 2:19:45.207
<i>I hate him.</i>

2:19:45.680 --> 2:19:47.523
I'll take care of Koontz, Henry.

2:19:56.640 --> 2:19:58.005
Lead the way, Henry.

2:19:59.840 --> 2:20:01.080
Lead the way.

2:20:20.920 --> 2:20:22.729
All right, dog meat, I've had it.

2:20:22.880 --> 2:20:24.325
Your head's
gonna be bouncing off the floor...

2:20:57.080 --> 2:20:59.321
No, no, no, Mike. No, no, no.

2:21:00.360 --> 2:21:02.727
I will have no need of this stuff, Mike.

2:21:02.880 --> 2:21:06.362
Thank you very much for thinking
about me and including it just in case.

2:21:06.560 --> 2:21:09.211
But none for me, thank you very much!

2:21:09.360 --> 2:21:11.328
- Richie, you're shouting.
- What? I know!

2:21:11.560 --> 2:21:14.006
Beep, beep, Richie. Beep, beep.

2:21:14.800 --> 2:21:17.167
Talk to us, Mike. Tell us stories.

2:21:17.400 --> 2:21:21.007
Tell us things so we don't have to
remember what we just saw in the library.

2:21:22.840 --> 2:21:27.129
Hey, Eddie. Come on, pal.
Don't let it get you. Fight it.

2:21:28.880 --> 2:21:32.248
I saw myself today.
I saw myself back there.

2:21:32.920 --> 2:21:36.402
I know it's just camphor water,
I know that, but I need it anyway.

2:21:36.680 --> 2:21:38.364
Take it easy, pal.

2:21:38.640 --> 2:21:41.689
If it works, Eddie, it's good medicine.
You've always believed in it,

2:21:41.840 --> 2:21:43.922
- that's all that ever mattered.
- Thanks.

2:21:46.080 --> 2:21:49.641
I'm sure by now you all remember
what was going on in Derry 30 years ago.

2:21:50.120 --> 2:21:54.603
There was a rash of killings, maimings,
disappearances, mostly of children.

2:21:54.760 --> 2:21:57.570
Everybody was afraid,
but nobody did anything.

2:21:58.440 --> 2:22:00.090
Until we went after it.

2:22:03.600 --> 2:22:04.840
<i>We almost killed it.</i>

2:22:07.600 --> 2:22:10.410
Henry Bowers confessed to everything
and the killings stopped.

2:22:10.720 --> 2:22:13.405
Until earlier this year,
exactly 30 years later.

2:22:13.680 --> 2:22:15.284
<i>Now, the first thing you should know is,</i>

2:22:15.440 --> 2:22:17.044
if you count backwards
in 30-year increments,

2:22:17.200 --> 2:22:21.603
every date you come to will correspond
to a huge disaster in Derry's history.

2:22:21.920 --> 2:22:24.161
<i>In 1960, the big fire
at the Black Spot Club.</i>

2:22:24.360 --> 2:22:27.091
In 1930, the explosion
down at the old ironworks.

2:22:27.280 --> 2:22:30.727
In 1900, the massacre at Drake's Creek.
And on, and on.

2:22:31.680 --> 2:22:37.403
The biggest mystery is how 253 settlers
just disappeared without a trace.

2:22:37.960 --> 2:22:42.841
Thank you, Michael, for that illuminating,
if somewhat morbid, history.

2:22:43.600 --> 2:22:45.329
<i>She didn't want to know.</i>

2:22:45.520 --> 2:22:47.409
You knew all about this, even then.

2:22:47.560 --> 2:22:49.528
Miss Douglas didn't want to know.

2:22:49.680 --> 2:22:51.569
It's a disease, Bev.

2:22:52.320 --> 2:22:54.561
The Derry disease.
None of them wants to know.

2:22:54.760 --> 2:22:58.321
- It's too horrible so they act like...
- They act like it didn't even happen.

2:22:58.480 --> 2:23:01.848
I remember a man, Mr. Ross,

2:23:02.920 --> 2:23:07.164
he was on his front porch,
I was coming home from school.

2:23:07.680 --> 2:23:11.321
<i>Henry Bowers was waiting
right outside my house.</i>

2:23:13.840 --> 2:23:16.730
<i>I saw Mr. Ross across the street.</i>

2:23:17.280 --> 2:23:21.683
<i>He looked so concerned,
I thought he was going to help me,</i>

2:23:22.520 --> 2:23:26.241
<i>but I couldn't believe it,
he just turned around and went inside.</i>

2:23:33.680 --> 2:23:35.330
<i>That was when it really hit me</i>

2:23:35.480 --> 2:23:38.484
there was something
terribly wrong in Derry, with Derry.

2:23:39.280 --> 2:23:41.328
How did you get out of that, Bev?

2:23:41.880 --> 2:23:46.044
Daddy came home, one of the only times
I was ever really glad to see him.

2:23:48.360 --> 2:23:52.968
So, it's 30 years later and right
on schedule the killings start up again.

2:23:53.240 --> 2:23:54.571
Six so far, maybe more.

2:23:54.880 --> 2:23:57.724
<i>There have been a number of disappearances
with no trace of a body.</i>

2:23:58.320 --> 2:24:01.369
I wanted to be absolutely certain
before I called anyone.

2:24:01.600 --> 2:24:03.045
And I became absolutely certain

2:24:03.200 --> 2:24:05.362
when I found something
at the latest crime site.

2:24:05.880 --> 2:24:07.962
God, that was just yesterday.

2:24:10.400 --> 2:24:12.880
Anyway, this is it.

2:24:18.680 --> 2:24:19.886
Georgie?

2:24:26.400 --> 2:24:27.401
For whatever reason,

2:24:27.600 --> 2:24:30.251
there's something
very special about us being together.

2:24:30.560 --> 2:24:33.962
We found each other that summer
and our togetherness made us strong.

2:24:34.120 --> 2:24:37.363
Otherwise, it would have picked us off,
one by one.

2:24:37.840 --> 2:24:38.966
Think about it.

2:24:39.120 --> 2:24:41.043
Is it an accident
that none of us have kids?

2:24:41.200 --> 2:24:42.440
Including Stan.

2:24:42.800 --> 2:24:45.610
Or that when we came together
as young people,

2:24:45.760 --> 2:24:47.489
we were all losers.

2:24:49.920 --> 2:24:51.365
<i>Now look at you.</i>

2:24:52.120 --> 2:24:54.851
Six of you left Derry
and became unusually successful.

2:24:55.040 --> 2:24:56.280
Big-time breadwinners.

2:24:56.440 --> 2:24:57.851
Leaving you here holding the bag.

2:24:58.040 --> 2:25:00.042
Yeah. You kept the lighthouse
for the rest of us.

2:25:00.200 --> 2:25:01.964
I feel like a real jerk about that, Mike.

2:25:02.120 --> 2:25:03.121
Me, too.

2:25:03.440 --> 2:25:04.680
It's nobody's fault.

2:25:04.880 --> 2:25:08.123
Our parents decided
who stayed and who went.

2:25:08.440 --> 2:25:11.011
When I grew up, I stayed here
because I wanted to.

2:25:11.200 --> 2:25:13.328
I think you stayed because you had to.

2:25:14.280 --> 2:25:16.806
I don't know what's gonna happen
when the sun comes up,

2:25:17.000 --> 2:25:20.129
but I do know that I appreciate
what you've done for everyone.

2:25:44.120 --> 2:25:47.329
Good evening. You're up late.
- How much farther is Derry?

2:25:47.800 --> 2:25:48.801
Oh...

2:25:49.280 --> 2:25:53.330
I guess about maybe
500 yards to the city limits.

2:25:53.640 --> 2:25:57.087
Oh, thank God.
I nearly fell asleep a while ago.

2:25:57.240 --> 2:25:58.924
I feel like I've been driving forever.

2:25:59.440 --> 2:26:02.205
Just cross the old bridge down there
at the barrens and hang a left.

2:26:02.520 --> 2:26:03.567
The barrens?

2:26:04.000 --> 2:26:06.287
Yes, where
they used to play when they were kids.

2:26:09.360 --> 2:26:12.204
Thank you. I'll be going now.

2:26:15.280 --> 2:26:18.011
Don't you want your balloon first,
Mrs. Denbrough?

2:26:18.840 --> 2:26:20.046
Don't you want it?

2:26:22.240 --> 2:26:23.287
Don't you want it?

2:26:24.680 --> 2:26:25.727
<i>Don't you want it?</i>

2:26:26.960 --> 2:26:28.166
Don't you want it?

2:26:28.560 --> 2:26:29.721
<i>Don't you want it?</i>

2:26:30.120 --> 2:26:31.360
Don't you want it?

2:26:31.760 --> 2:26:32.921
<i>Don't you want it?</i>

2:26:34.800 --> 2:26:36.006
<i>Don't you want it?</i>

2:26:38.240 --> 2:26:40.368
<i>They chased me up the hall,
past the lockers,</i>

2:26:40.560 --> 2:26:42.403
<i>they got me down
and they started slapping me.</i>

2:26:42.680 --> 2:26:45.604
<i>The coach found me lying there,
I was crying,</i>

2:26:45.760 --> 2:26:47.364
<i>and I thought he was gonna help me.</i>

2:26:47.720 --> 2:26:51.122
But instead, he just made fun of me
and something inside snapped. I got mad.

2:26:51.320 --> 2:26:52.890
I said, "Coach, you coach track, right?"

2:26:53.040 --> 2:26:55.486
He sort of sneered at me and nodded,
and I said,

2:26:55.680 --> 2:26:57.728
"Well, you listen to me,
you stone-brained son of a bitch,

2:26:57.880 --> 2:26:59.245
"I'm gonna go out for
the track team in March

2:26:59.400 --> 2:27:00.811
"and I'm gonna run down
everything you got.

2:27:00.960 --> 2:27:02.166
"I'm gonna run down your best

2:27:02.320 --> 2:27:05.051
"and then
I want a flipping apology from you."

2:27:05.320 --> 2:27:06.446
All right.

2:27:07.160 --> 2:27:08.400
And so you did it?

2:27:08.560 --> 2:27:10.244
Yeah, I ran everywhere.

2:27:10.400 --> 2:27:13.768
Sometimes, my heart felt like it was
pounding so hard I was gonna pass out.

2:27:13.920 --> 2:27:15.763
And the first time I ran a mile,
I puked, then fainted.

2:27:17.160 --> 2:27:19.208
<i>Finally, I was holding up
my pants as I ran.</i>

2:27:19.360 --> 2:27:21.362
I mean, I ate salads
like there was no tomorrow.

2:27:21.560 --> 2:27:25.281
By March, I'd lost 70 pounds
and I'd grown two inches.

2:27:25.560 --> 2:27:27.722
Every time I ran, I felt like I could fly.

2:27:27.880 --> 2:27:30.486
- And you went out?
- I went out for track just like I said.

2:27:30.640 --> 2:27:33.450
First day I was out there
I won the 220 and the 440.

2:27:33.600 --> 2:27:35.250
I just blew away the coaches. Best guys.

2:27:35.400 --> 2:27:37.084
After practice,
I walked right up to the coach

2:27:37.280 --> 2:27:40.124
and I asked for that apology.
He was so furious, he hit me.

2:27:40.280 --> 2:27:42.089
- No! After all that...
- It was perfect!

2:27:42.240 --> 2:27:44.527
- You beat him!
- And everybody knew it.

2:27:44.960 --> 2:27:47.611
I graduated from El Paso High
with a letter in track.

2:27:47.760 --> 2:27:51.321
And the coach lost his job
over that little love tap.

2:27:52.640 --> 2:27:54.847
That's great, Ben.
You ought to write that one down.

2:27:55.000 --> 2:27:57.446
- Bill's our writer.
- I just write horror stories.

2:27:57.600 --> 2:27:59.568
You know, we still haven't talked
about what we're going to do,

2:27:59.760 --> 2:28:00.761
if we're gonna do anything.

2:28:01.480 --> 2:28:04.051
On, Mikey, Mikey, Mikey...

2:28:04.880 --> 2:28:06.405
Listen, kids.

2:28:06.840 --> 2:28:08.808
This campfire stuff is fun, it really is,

2:28:08.960 --> 2:28:12.328
but it doesn't matter how painstakingly
we go over these sewer plans

2:28:12.480 --> 2:28:15.484
or how many damn flashlights
or helmets you got in that box.

2:28:15.640 --> 2:28:17.369
When the sun comes up, I'm dust,

2:28:17.560 --> 2:28:20.006
and I would suggest that
the rest of you follow me

2:28:20.200 --> 2:28:22.009
and get the hell out of Dodge!

2:28:22.480 --> 2:28:24.482
I cleaned it up once.
<i>Cleaned what?</i>

2:28:26.800 --> 2:28:27.961
The blood.

2:28:28.760 --> 2:28:31.286
I cleaned the whole thing up
that very same night.

2:29:02.200 --> 2:29:05.602
<i>I decided if I was ever
going to sleep in this house again,</i>

2:29:05.800 --> 2:29:07.040
<i>I'd have to know the truth.</i>

2:29:08.040 --> 2:29:10.361
<i>To see if anyone besides me
could see the blood.</i>

2:29:23.080 --> 2:29:25.890
What happened in here?
Somebody get murdered?

2:29:28.000 --> 2:29:30.890
You see it? You really see it?

2:29:34.880 --> 2:29:36.882
Come on, let's clean this up.

2:29:42.000 --> 2:29:45.721
<i>Until that moment,
I thought I was going crazy.</i>

2:29:45.880 --> 2:29:49.407
<i>It was so strange to be happy
about something so grim.</i>

2:29:50.240 --> 2:29:52.925
I fell in love with all of you guys
that day.

2:29:53.920 --> 2:29:56.571
And after we cleaned it up,
the blood never came back.

2:30:04.520 --> 2:30:06.204
It will be morning soon.

2:30:08.400 --> 2:30:10.562
- I'm cold.
- Me, too.

2:30:11.240 --> 2:30:13.925
- I'll get you something.
- There's a shawl in my room.

2:30:14.080 --> 2:30:16.924
Give me your room key and I'll get it.

2:30:17.640 --> 2:30:19.369
Richie, you have a key?

2:30:19.800 --> 2:30:21.086
<i>All right. Now, listen up.</i>

2:30:21.280 --> 2:30:23.282
Stay together, guys. No stragglers.

2:30:25.240 --> 2:30:28.289
Just get the first thing you find.
I need to stretch my legs anyway.

2:30:28.480 --> 2:30:29.527
Ben.

2:30:29.720 --> 2:30:32.564
- Don't go alone.
- Uh, I need a refill anyway.

2:30:33.560 --> 2:30:34.766
I'll join you.

2:30:47.240 --> 2:30:48.321
I'll take care of Richie.

2:30:48.480 --> 2:30:51.723
Okay. We meet back here in three minutes,
no more. Keep your doors open.

2:31:41.640 --> 2:31:45.122
Hello, nigger. I'll pay you back.

2:31:45.720 --> 2:31:47.051
I'm gonna pay you all back.

2:32:02.080 --> 2:32:03.570
Oh, good. You found it.

2:32:06.880 --> 2:32:10.680
I'm glad we're alone for a minute.
I've been wanting to say something to you.

2:32:13.360 --> 2:32:16.887
"Your hair is winter fire. January embers.

2:32:18.720 --> 2:32:21.724
- "My heart burns there, too."
- It was you.

2:32:22.880 --> 2:32:25.565
I've been waiting a long time
to thank the poet.

2:32:30.560 --> 2:32:32.847
- Did you ask Bill first?
- No.

2:32:33.560 --> 2:32:36.404
I knew it was you.
I've always known it was you.

2:32:38.040 --> 2:32:41.044
I think I must have been waiting, Ben,
waiting until we were both ready.

2:32:42.840 --> 2:32:44.365
I'm ready now. Are you?

2:32:56.240 --> 2:32:58.527
Oh, oh, Beverly.

2:33:15.760 --> 2:33:17.205
Kiss me, fat boy!

2:33:55.160 --> 2:33:56.400
Belch...

2:34:04.160 --> 2:34:06.162
Mike! Mike!

2:34:06.840 --> 2:34:07.966
Mike!

2:34:11.160 --> 2:34:12.969
You all right?
I got it.

2:34:16.480 --> 2:34:18.164
Get him in there.
Give me a hand.

2:34:18.720 --> 2:34:20.324
Watch it! Okay, easy.

2:34:23.880 --> 2:34:25.370
- In the car.
- Hurry up!

2:34:26.160 --> 2:34:27.764
Go! Go! Go!
No, Mike!

2:35:04.040 --> 2:35:06.566
<i>If Mike dies,
there will be five of us left.</i>

2:35:08.120 --> 2:35:10.566
Who comes next? Which one of us?

2:35:12.840 --> 2:35:14.524
Why is it doing this?

2:35:15.400 --> 2:35:16.731
Why does It hate?

2:35:17.480 --> 2:35:19.562
Why is It so mean?

2:35:28.880 --> 2:35:30.245
Oh, Ben.

2:35:32.920 --> 2:35:34.524
I want to tell you something.

2:35:35.280 --> 2:35:37.169
You remember what my father was like?

2:35:39.000 --> 2:35:41.606
I fell in love with a man

2:35:41.760 --> 2:35:45.890
who turned out to be everything
I always hated in my father.

2:35:49.280 --> 2:35:52.966
Why would I do that?
How could I be so blind?

2:35:54.440 --> 2:35:58.729
If you see it now,
you're not blind anymore, Bev.

2:36:00.040 --> 2:36:01.929
Congratulations. That's a miracle.

2:36:03.320 --> 2:36:05.846
Besides, at least you fell in love
with somebody.

2:36:07.400 --> 2:36:10.131
At least you felt something.

2:36:11.440 --> 2:36:12.930
That's a miracle, too.

2:36:14.280 --> 2:36:16.248
You have the heart of a poet, Ben.

2:36:20.440 --> 2:36:22.442
"Your hair is winter fire."

2:36:25.120 --> 2:36:27.726
- Why did you say that?
- You wrote it, didn't you?

2:36:28.200 --> 2:36:30.885
"Your hair is winter fire.
January embers." Something.

2:36:31.600 --> 2:36:33.967
When I was young, I thought it was Bill,
but it was you, wasn't it?

2:36:34.120 --> 2:36:36.327
Damn it, Bev, is that you in there
or is that the clown?

2:36:36.480 --> 2:36:38.767
I don't know what the hell is going on!
How am I supposed to know?

2:36:38.960 --> 2:36:39.961
It's me.

2:36:41.400 --> 2:36:42.731
It's me.

2:36:55.000 --> 2:36:57.002
"My heart burns there, too."

2:37:32.560 --> 2:37:34.642
Mike's gonna be okay.
Can we see him?

2:37:34.920 --> 2:37:36.046
He's not out of the woods yet.

2:37:36.200 --> 2:37:38.521
I guess one of you could go in
for just a minute.

2:37:48.760 --> 2:37:49.841
Mike?

2:37:51.600 --> 2:37:53.443
Everyone else is right outside.

2:37:54.680 --> 2:37:56.842
- Henry?
- He's dead.

2:37:58.520 --> 2:37:59.885
- Police?
- Not yet.

2:38:01.960 --> 2:38:04.042
Be careful. We can't trust anyone.

2:38:04.560 --> 2:38:07.006
If anybody asks, a party got out of hand.

2:38:07.200 --> 2:38:09.248
You were dancing on the table,
you took a fall.

2:38:10.720 --> 2:38:13.041
Anyone who's seen me dance will buy that.

2:38:14.760 --> 2:38:17.730
- What are you going to do?
- I don't know, man.

2:38:18.080 --> 2:38:19.764
I honestly do not know.

2:38:20.880 --> 2:38:22.882
My jacket. Outside pocket.

2:38:34.240 --> 2:38:36.402
<i>It's silver. It can kill It.</i>

2:38:38.080 --> 2:38:40.082
But we left these down in the...

2:38:43.760 --> 2:38:45.091
You went back?

2:38:46.800 --> 2:38:48.768
I was pretty sure it was asleep.

2:38:49.640 --> 2:38:51.085
"Pretty sure"?

2:38:52.120 --> 2:38:53.360
You went alone?

2:38:54.440 --> 2:38:58.047
Ten years ago my life was going downhill.
I was close to suicide.

2:38:58.840 --> 2:39:01.161
I think I really wanted It
to wake up and kill me.

2:39:01.440 --> 2:39:03.841
<i>Took me all day
stumbling around in the dark.</i>

2:39:04.000 --> 2:39:05.081
<i>I found one right away.</i>

2:39:05.680 --> 2:39:07.011
In the drain trap.

2:39:07.280 --> 2:39:10.682
The other one, the one that hit Pennywise,
was lodged in a crack in the wall.

2:39:13.280 --> 2:39:15.965
I figured we might need that kind of help
again one day.

2:39:17.360 --> 2:39:19.886
When I came out,
I kind of I got my life together.

2:39:21.560 --> 2:39:23.085
The only change was this.

2:39:23.800 --> 2:39:25.040
Almost overnight.

2:39:28.160 --> 2:39:29.321
Fear.

2:39:31.600 --> 2:39:32.647
Bill.

2:39:33.320 --> 2:39:35.163
If you decide not use those,

2:39:35.800 --> 2:39:38.724
if you leave, I'll understand.

2:39:45.520 --> 2:39:47.284
People, that is a dead body.

2:39:47.440 --> 2:39:50.603
You're not seriously suggesting we walk
out of here and leave it lying there?

2:39:50.760 --> 2:39:51.886
Yeah. That's what I'm suggesting.

2:39:52.040 --> 2:39:54.566
- I think we ought to call the police.
- I think Eddie's right.

2:39:54.720 --> 2:39:58.406
You don't understand. This whole town
is It in some way. All of them.

2:40:09.200 --> 2:40:10.486
Bill's right.

2:40:10.960 --> 2:40:12.962
If we call the police,
get the town involved,

2:40:13.160 --> 2:40:14.889
something bad's going to
happen to one of us.

2:40:15.080 --> 2:40:16.366
Maybe all of us.

2:40:16.840 --> 2:40:21.528
All right. Have it your way. Stan is dead.
Mike came close. I've seen enough.

2:40:21.680 --> 2:40:22.681
I'm with you, boy.

2:40:22.880 --> 2:40:24.769
You can put this behind you
just like that?

2:40:24.920 --> 2:40:27.366
I'm a little old
for monster hunting, Bill.

2:40:27.520 --> 2:40:28.521
So was Mike.

2:40:28.920 --> 2:40:30.251
So was Stan.

2:40:31.040 --> 2:40:33.088
- Is that how you feel, Ben?
- I don't know how I feel.

2:40:33.240 --> 2:40:35.208
All I know is, I can't stay
in this room much longer.

2:40:35.360 --> 2:40:39.524
So I suggest we just turn on the TV,
hang a "Do not disturb" sign on the door,

2:40:39.720 --> 2:40:42.007
go outside, then figure out what to do.

2:40:42.320 --> 2:40:43.731
I second that.

2:40:55.840 --> 2:40:58.730
<i>Police Chief Andrew Rademacher
of the downtown branch said the victim,</i>

2:40:58.880 --> 2:41:00.086
<i>5-year-old Danielle Huxton,</i>

2:41:00.240 --> 2:41:02.242
<i>had been playing
at the creek near her home.</i>

2:41:02.560 --> 2:41:05.450
<i>Local authorities have not yet said
whether there might be a connection</i>

2:41:05.600 --> 2:41:08.968
<i>between this and a recent rash of
disappearances involving young children.</i>

2:41:09.440 --> 2:41:12.444
<i>They did reveal, however,
that the body was severely mutilated.</i>

2:41:13.200 --> 2:41:15.771
<i>In other news tonight,
a series of robberies in the east end</i>

2:41:15.920 --> 2:41:17.081
<i>has local officials baffled...</i>

2:41:19.760 --> 2:41:22.684
Appreciate it if you just
put that on my card, send me a receipt.

2:41:22.840 --> 2:41:24.490
- Oh, certainly, Mr. Hanscom.
- Me, too, thank you.

2:41:24.680 --> 2:41:26.569
- Ditto, thanks.
- Nice time, loads of fun. Got to go, bye.

2:42:13.560 --> 2:42:14.721
Need a ride, Bill?

2:42:15.000 --> 2:42:17.082
- Where are you going, Richie?
- Airport.

2:42:17.640 --> 2:42:20.041
- I guess we are, too, Bill.
- Come with us.

2:42:21.000 --> 2:42:24.641
I just saw something
and I have no idea if it was real.

2:42:26.160 --> 2:42:28.481
<i>If any of you would have seen it or not.</i>

2:42:30.000 --> 2:42:31.081
I can't go.

2:42:32.360 --> 2:42:35.443
Because if I do, I'm gonna
live with this until I go insane.

2:42:36.360 --> 2:42:40.206
Until I can't tell the difference
between my life and my bad dreams.

2:42:41.520 --> 2:42:43.761
For years I've been getting paid
to scare people.

2:42:45.920 --> 2:42:47.843
But I'm the one who's been scared.

2:42:49.560 --> 2:42:50.891
All my life.

2:42:52.480 --> 2:42:54.448
I don't want to be scared anymore.

2:42:57.120 --> 2:42:58.451
I'm going back in.

2:43:02.000 --> 2:43:03.650
This time I'm gonna kill It.

2:43:04.280 --> 2:43:05.327
<i>Help me!</i>

2:43:06.480 --> 2:43:07.481
<i>Help me!</i>

2:43:11.280 --> 2:43:12.964
Please, help me.

2:44:17.960 --> 2:44:20.406
I don't suppose anybody thought
to bring anything really useful,

2:44:20.560 --> 2:44:21.800
like a machine gun?

2:44:21.960 --> 2:44:24.440
I brought this. It's the only thing
I saved from those days.

2:44:24.840 --> 2:44:27.320
- I remember you were a dead shot, Bev.
- You couldn't miss.

2:44:27.480 --> 2:44:29.767
It was like it was supposed
to be Bev, remember?

2:44:29.960 --> 2:44:32.122
You hit the clown, Pennywise,
in the head, it broke open.

2:44:32.280 --> 2:44:34.442
- And underneath it was a light.
- Bright lights.

2:44:34.600 --> 2:44:36.523
Deadlights. We saw them, too,
for a second.

2:44:36.720 --> 2:44:37.801
Bev?

2:44:37.960 --> 2:44:40.964
- Bill, how on earth...
- Mike went back down and got them.

2:44:41.960 --> 2:44:44.645
These are for him and for Stan.

2:44:46.800 --> 2:44:48.802
- Lucky seven.
- We're all here now.

2:44:50.320 --> 2:44:54.370
Oh, come on, guys. What the hell are you
going to do now? Sing <i>Kumbaya?</i>

2:44:54.960 --> 2:44:58.646
Wake up. Take a breath. Do you smell that?

2:44:58.920 --> 2:44:59.967
That's death.

2:45:00.160 --> 2:45:02.891
It's not for Mike, it's not for Stan,
it's not for Henry Bowers.

2:45:03.080 --> 2:45:04.809
It's for us. It's in the air.

2:45:04.960 --> 2:45:08.760
Losers fight It, losers die.
And you know that, don't you, Captain?

2:45:09.400 --> 2:45:12.244
- You don't have to go down there, Richie.
- Right.

2:45:12.400 --> 2:45:13.765
I didn't have to get on a plane in LA,

2:45:13.960 --> 2:45:16.531
I didn't have to go to the dinner,
I sure as hell didn't have to come here.

2:45:16.680 --> 2:45:18.364
And now I don't have to go in.

2:45:24.960 --> 2:45:27.361
I still say we should have brought
a machine gun.

2:46:35.120 --> 2:46:39.444
I remember the first thing I saw down here
was one of those damn pom-poms.

2:46:45.480 --> 2:46:49.769
- This purse looks new.
- Oh, dear God. It's not possible.

2:46:50.240 --> 2:46:51.924
- Audra.
- What?

2:46:52.120 --> 2:46:54.930
How in God's name...
She's down here.

2:46:55.240 --> 2:46:56.287
- His wife?
- It's got her.

2:46:56.560 --> 2:46:58.324
- How could she...
- it could be a trick or something.

2:46:58.920 --> 2:47:00.285
Bill, wait, damn it!

2:47:00.440 --> 2:47:01.646
Audra!

2:47:16.200 --> 2:47:18.168
Audra. Audra.

2:47:18.360 --> 2:47:20.203
<i>Bill.
Come back, Bill!</i>

2:47:21.960 --> 2:47:24.281
- Do you want to get yourself killed?
- Oh, God, Bill!

2:47:24.480 --> 2:47:26.209
God, Bill, you all right?

2:47:27.080 --> 2:47:30.562
It's my fault. She followed me.

2:47:32.520 --> 2:47:33.965
I told her...
Bill, that's enough!

2:47:34.160 --> 2:47:36.686
If she is down here,
there's only one way you can help her.

2:47:37.280 --> 2:47:40.443
Now you know what we came down here for
and we're going to do it.

2:47:40.600 --> 2:47:44.321
Now, we need you. We need you
to stand up for us like before,

2:47:44.480 --> 2:47:46.050
or none of us is going to get out of here.

2:47:57.800 --> 2:47:59.040
Come on.

2:48:05.000 --> 2:48:06.411
Stay close together.

2:48:24.600 --> 2:48:27.570
- Looks like we're off the map.
- I think...

2:48:29.440 --> 2:48:30.646
That way.

2:49:07.160 --> 2:49:08.525
We're here.

2:49:10.480 --> 2:49:12.960
The roots all grow down.
Yeah.

2:49:13.160 --> 2:49:15.891
- Yeah, the walls cracked, remember?
- When It came.

2:49:16.080 --> 2:49:18.731
Dear God, please don't let these things
come to life.

2:49:18.880 --> 2:49:20.803
Don't you even think that, spaghetti man.

2:49:21.000 --> 2:49:22.968
I told you not to call me "spaghetti man."

2:49:23.120 --> 2:49:25.646
I think something is coming.

2:50:02.960 --> 2:50:04.849
- My boat.
- Georgie.

2:50:05.920 --> 2:50:07.285
It's all your fault.

2:50:07.680 --> 2:50:09.569
Oh... Georgie.

2:50:09.840 --> 2:50:13.481
All your fault, Bill.
You sent me out and It killed me.

2:50:14.240 --> 2:50:18.040
No. No, Georgie. I didn't know.

2:50:18.200 --> 2:50:21.647
Bill, remember, that's not Georgie.
Remember. Fight it!

2:50:22.280 --> 2:50:23.964
It was in the drain, Bill.

2:50:24.200 --> 2:50:26.851
It was in the drain.
And you let It kill me.

2:50:27.600 --> 2:50:30.126
No. I loved you.

2:50:30.320 --> 2:50:31.810
Damn it, Bill,
that thing's not your brother.

2:50:31.960 --> 2:50:33.803
Come on, man.
Fight it.

2:50:36.240 --> 2:50:39.050
You are not George.

2:50:41.480 --> 2:50:43.244
George is dead,

2:50:44.000 --> 2:50:45.604
and it's not my fault.

2:50:54.160 --> 2:50:56.731
You killed my brother, George,
you bastard.

2:50:57.160 --> 2:50:58.685
Let's see you now.

2:51:00.160 --> 2:51:01.366
<i>Let's see you now.</i>

2:51:02.840 --> 2:51:04.330
Show yourself.

2:51:09.360 --> 2:51:11.362
You killed my little brother

2:51:12.520 --> 2:51:14.568
and now you're going to pay.

2:51:20.480 --> 2:51:23.404
<i>Go while you still can.</i>

2:51:25.200 --> 2:51:28.522
<i>This is your last chance.</i>

2:51:29.200 --> 2:51:30.531
Show yourself.

2:51:33.520 --> 2:51:35.010
<i>Silly boy.</i>

2:51:35.320 --> 2:51:39.041
You still think you can see me.

2:51:41.640 --> 2:51:43.085
You'll never see me.

2:51:43.240 --> 2:51:46.926
<i>You'll see only
what your little mind can allow.</i>

2:51:47.440 --> 2:51:49.602
Go! Now.

2:51:49.920 --> 2:51:51.763
For if you stay,

2:51:52.400 --> 2:51:54.721
you'll lose your little mind

2:51:55.120 --> 2:51:58.044
in my deadlights.

2:51:58.880 --> 2:52:00.291
<i>Like all the others.</i>

2:52:01.240 --> 2:52:03.402
Like all the others.

2:52:22.920 --> 2:52:27.881
Bill. We can't fight that thing.
That's like trying to fight smoke.

2:52:28.120 --> 2:52:30.771
Don't you understand
what Mike was trying to tell us?

2:52:31.240 --> 2:52:33.083
It feeds, Richie.

2:52:33.560 --> 2:52:36.609
It wakes up every 30 years and it feeds.

2:52:36.920 --> 2:52:41.164
And in order to feed, it has
to take on some kind of physical form.

2:52:43.120 --> 2:52:44.451
It's here.

2:52:45.800 --> 2:52:47.882
Down here. Somewhere.

2:53:57.160 --> 2:53:58.685
Fee, fi, fo, fum.

2:53:59.840 --> 2:54:01.729
- You think we're strong enough?
- We have to be.

2:54:01.880 --> 2:54:04.247
I have to tell you guys something
before we go in there.

2:54:04.440 --> 2:54:06.090
- Eddie?
- Yeah.

2:54:07.960 --> 2:54:09.689
- I've been lying.
- About what?

2:54:10.360 --> 2:54:12.362
When I said that I was seeing someone.

2:54:13.280 --> 2:54:16.568
Well, I'm not. In fact, I haven't ever...

2:54:17.880 --> 2:54:20.531
I mean, I've never even been with any...

2:54:20.840 --> 2:54:22.968
Eddie, what are you saying?
You're a virgin?

2:54:23.320 --> 2:54:24.367
Yeah.

2:54:25.200 --> 2:54:27.680
Well, I can't help you with that, pal.
But thanks for sharing.

2:54:27.840 --> 2:54:29.285
Richie, let him talk.

2:54:31.720 --> 2:54:33.051
You see...

2:54:33.560 --> 2:54:36.882
I could never sleep
with somebody that I didn't love.

2:54:37.480 --> 2:54:39.960
And I've never really loved anyone.

2:54:42.240 --> 2:54:43.844
Except you guys.

2:54:45.560 --> 2:54:46.561
Hey.

2:55:44.720 --> 2:55:46.165
<i>Oh, my God.</i>

2:55:58.480 --> 2:56:00.323
A body.

2:56:05.320 --> 2:56:06.481
Audra.

2:56:07.160 --> 2:56:09.162
- Bill, for God's sake!
- Wait for us, buddy.

2:56:09.400 --> 2:56:11.164
It's Audra. I'm going to get her.

2:56:40.600 --> 2:56:41.886
Bill...

2:56:47.840 --> 2:56:49.171
I damn you to hell.

2:56:58.960 --> 2:57:00.200
Please, dear God!

2:57:02.120 --> 2:57:07.286
"He thrusts his fists against the posts,

2:57:07.440 --> 2:57:11.889
"and still insists he sees the ghosts."

2:57:30.800 --> 2:57:32.962
It's taking him. Bill!

2:57:38.640 --> 2:57:40.768
Come on, guys! We got to...

2:57:45.120 --> 2:57:47.805
Bev! Bev, where are you going? Bev...

2:57:51.320 --> 2:57:52.731
Bev...

2:57:52.880 --> 2:57:54.769
What am I going to do?

2:57:56.080 --> 2:57:58.401
This is battery acid, you slime!

2:58:10.920 --> 2:58:15.005
I believe in Santa Claus.
I believe in the Easter Bunny.

2:58:16.640 --> 2:58:18.483
I believe in the Tooth Fairy.

2:58:19.160 --> 2:58:20.605
But I don't believe in you.

2:58:22.160 --> 2:58:25.767
This is battery acid. Now you disappear.

2:58:44.440 --> 2:58:46.568
Please, God, don't let me miss again.

2:59:15.920 --> 2:59:17.490
Eddie? Eddie.

2:59:20.520 --> 2:59:22.010
Hey...

2:59:22.160 --> 2:59:23.525
Nice shot, Bev.

2:59:23.840 --> 2:59:26.844
Don't you talk. Don't talk.
You're gonna be fine, spaghetti man.

2:59:28.360 --> 2:59:30.010
Richie, please...

2:59:30.160 --> 2:59:33.164
For the last time, don't call me that.

2:59:35.600 --> 2:59:37.409
You know how I...

2:59:41.840 --> 2:59:43.046
Eddie.

2:59:46.760 --> 2:59:48.046
Eddie.

3:00:03.640 --> 3:00:05.210
This isn't over.

3:00:05.800 --> 3:00:08.041
If that thing comes back when I'm 70...

3:00:08.200 --> 3:00:10.407
Let's finish it. Once and for all.

3:01:19.960 --> 3:01:20.961
Audra.

3:01:34.320 --> 3:01:35.810
It's all coming down.

3:02:20.720 --> 3:02:22.529
<i>I guess that's how
I'd like to remember us,</i>

3:02:22.680 --> 3:02:24.011
<i>if I could remember us.</i>

3:02:24.200 --> 3:02:27.921
<i>Standing there by the lake
with the sun going down on our childhood.</i>

3:02:28.120 --> 3:02:31.363
<i>This will be my last entry.
I got it in just in time.</i>

3:02:31.520 --> 3:02:35.047
<i>Just before the fog in my brain
swept all of my memories away entirely.</i>

3:02:38.360 --> 3:02:40.488
<i>Now, just weeks later,
I look back on that time</i>

3:02:40.640 --> 3:02:43.325
<i>not from memory,
but from the pages of this book.</i>

3:02:43.480 --> 3:02:44.720
<i>The nightmare is over.</i>

3:02:44.880 --> 3:02:47.850
<i>What little police involvement there was
was brief and cursory.</i>

3:02:48.000 --> 3:02:50.048
<i>As is always the case here in Derry.</i>

3:02:51.120 --> 3:02:53.600
<i>Now that there's no further need
for a lighthouse keeper...</i>

3:02:53.760 --> 3:02:57.446
<i>Well, I feel I may move on,
see whatever's down the road apiece.</i>

3:02:58.400 --> 3:03:01.165
<i>As of this writing,
Richie's still knocking them dead.</i>

3:03:01.360 --> 3:03:02.407
<i>He's got a part in a movie.</i>

3:03:03.480 --> 3:03:05.448
574. Take 18, mark.

3:03:05.600 --> 3:03:07.011
<i>He costars with another comic,</i>

3:03:07.200 --> 3:03:09.248
<i>a guy any of the lucky seven
could have told you</i>

3:03:09.400 --> 3:03:11.402
<i>looks and acts a lot like Eddie Kaspbrak.</i>

3:03:14.800 --> 3:03:15.881
<i>And cut.</i>

3:03:17.200 --> 3:03:19.885
<i>Ben and Bev left Derry together,
headed west.</i>

3:03:20.040 --> 3:03:23.328
<i>After a week, they were married.
A few weeks later, they were pregnant.</i>

3:03:23.480 --> 3:03:25.084
<i>Another curse broken.</i>

3:03:31.680 --> 3:03:34.763
<i>Bill and Audra are still here.
I wish the news were better.</i>

3:03:34.920 --> 3:03:38.561
<i>But Audra's condition is unchanged.
They're leaving today.</i>

3:03:40.640 --> 3:03:42.927
Okay, Audra. It's time to go.

3:03:43.080 --> 3:03:45.082
<i>Bill thought the time here,
the time away from his work,</i>

3:03:45.280 --> 3:03:46.486
<i>might somehow help.</i>

3:03:46.800 --> 3:03:50.646
<i>But I guess Audra's gone for good.
One of It's many casualties.</i>

3:03:51.120 --> 3:03:54.567
<i>Locked in that haunted place
where she saw Its deadlights.</i>

3:03:54.720 --> 3:03:58.611
<i>Bill has been good to visit every day.
We laugh about our failing memories.</i>

3:03:59.080 --> 3:04:01.048
<i>We sometimes have to ask
each other's names now.</i>

3:04:02.000 --> 3:04:05.561
<i>His sadness is profound.
I wish there was something I could do.</i>

3:04:05.760 --> 3:04:07.524
<i>Something I could have done.</i>

3:04:15.680 --> 3:04:18.604
<i>Hi yo, Silver. Away!</i>

3:04:19.600 --> 3:04:20.681
Wait.

3:04:23.120 --> 3:04:28.809
Audra, this bike saved
little Stan's life once. Mine, too.

3:04:29.160 --> 3:04:31.481
We were going so fast,
I think we beat the devil.

3:04:32.400 --> 3:04:34.846
I don't know if I can go that fast again.

3:04:35.280 --> 3:04:36.486
Hold on.

3:04:50.840 --> 3:04:51.841
Beat it.

3:04:52.200 --> 3:04:54.407
Beat it. Beat it. Beat it, Audra.

3:04:54.600 --> 3:04:57.126
Beat it. Beat it.

3:05:05.640 --> 3:05:07.369
Come on. Come on.

3:05:21.520 --> 3:05:22.726
- Bill?
- Yes.

3:05:22.920 --> 3:05:25.048
- Bill, where are we? What are we doing?
- Yes, it's okay.

3:05:25.200 --> 3:05:26.406
It's okay. Hang on.

3:05:26.560 --> 3:05:28.050
Just hang on, babe, it's okay.
